WEBVTT

00:23.691 --> 00:25.326
(CLOCKS TICKING)

01:32.193 --> 01:33.761
ANNOUNCER: October is
inventory time,

01:33.794 --> 01:35.729
so right now,
Statler Toyota

01:35.763 --> 01:37.565
is making the best
deals of the year

01:37.598 --> 01:39.700
on all
1985-model Toyotas.

01:39.733 --> 01:41.235
You won't find a better car

01:43.271 --> 01:44.905
at a better price
with better service
anywhere in Hill Valley.

01:44.938 --> 01:47.541
That's Statler Toyota
in downtown Hill Valley.

01:51.545 --> 01:54.548
NEWSCASTER:
The Senate is expected
to vote on this today.

01:54.582 --> 01:58.652
In other news,
officials at the Pacific
Nuclear research facility

01:58.686 --> 02:01.455
have denied the rumor
that a case of
missing plutonium

02:01.489 --> 02:04.625
was in fact stolen
from their vault
two weeks ago.

02:04.658 --> 02:06.894
A Libyan terrorist group
had claimed responsibility

02:06.927 --> 02:08.529
for the alleged theft.
(ALARM RINGING)

02:08.562 --> 02:10.664
However,
officials now attribute

02:10.698 --> 02:13.734
the discrepancy to
a simple clerical error.

02:13.767 --> 02:16.637
The FBI, which is
investigating the matter,
had no comment.

02:23.744 --> 02:24.678
(BUZZER BLARES)

02:58.679 --> 02:59.713
MARTY: Hey, Doc?

03:02.583 --> 03:03.517
Doc?

03:04.885 --> 03:06.887
Hello! Anybody home?

03:06.920 --> 03:07.821
Einstein, come here, boy.

03:07.855 --> 03:08.722
(WHISTLES)

03:09.757 --> 03:11.292
What's going on? Oh, God.

03:12.526 --> 03:15.296
Oh, Jesus!

03:15.329 --> 03:17.898
That is disgusting.
Where the hell is he?

03:19.567 --> 03:21.302
(CLOCKS TICKING)

03:31.312 --> 03:32.746
(MACHINE HUMMING)

03:41.755 --> 03:43.524
(HUMMING GROWS LOUDER)

04:04.845 --> 04:06.714
(LOUD HUMMING)

04:15.823 --> 04:16.657
(ELECTRIC GUITAR NOTE PLAYS)

04:18.326 --> 04:18.992
(GRUNTS)

04:27.335 --> 04:28.569
(GROANING)

04:38.078 --> 04:39.279
Whoa!

04:42.416 --> 04:43.951
Rock 'n' roll.

04:43.984 --> 04:45.653
(ALARM RINGING)

04:52.593 --> 04:53.961
Yo.
DOC: Marty, is that you?

04:53.994 --> 04:56.096
Hey. Hey, Doc.
Where are you?

04:56.129 --> 04:57.931
Thank God
I've found you.

04:59.633 --> 04:59.667
Listen, can you meet me
at Twin Pines Mall
tonight at 1:15?

05:01.034 --> 05:01.068
I made a major breakthrough,
and I'll need your assistance.

05:01.969 --> 05:02.002
Wait a minute.
1:15 in the morning?

05:03.571 --> 05:03.804
Yeah.

05:04.338 --> 05:05.839
Doc, what's going on?

05:05.873 --> 05:07.841
Where you been all week?
Working.

05:07.875 --> 05:09.009
Where's Einstein?
Is he with you?

05:09.042 --> 05:11.379
Yeah, he's right here.

05:11.412 --> 05:13.981
You know, Doc,
you left your
equipment on all week.

05:14.014 --> 05:16.417
My equipment.
That reminds me, Marty.

05:16.650 --> 05:18.085
You better not hook up
to the amplifier.

05:18.118 --> 05:20.120
There's a slight
possibility of overload.

05:20.153 --> 05:23.056
Yeah. I'll keep that in mind.

05:23.090 --> 05:25.393
Good. I'll see you tonight.
Don't forget now.

05:25.626 --> 05:26.827
1:15 a.m.,
Twin Pines Mall.

05:26.860 --> 05:27.995
Right.

05:28.028 --> 05:29.697
(CLOCKS CHIMING)

05:29.730 --> 05:30.764
(CLOCKS CUCKOOING)

05:35.102 --> 05:36.670
Are those my clocks
I hear?

05:36.704 --> 05:39.940
Yeah, it's 8:00.

05:39.973 --> 05:42.410
Perfect!
My experiment worked!

05:42.643 --> 05:44.111
They're all exactly
25 minutes slow!

05:45.879 --> 05:48.416
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute, Doc.

05:48.449 --> 05:50.150
Are you telling
me that it's 8:25?

05:50.183 --> 05:52.152
Precisely.

05:52.185 --> 05:54.755
Damn!
I'm late for school.

05:59.059 --> 06:00.728
(MUSIC PLAYING)

06:55.248 --> 06:57.084
Jennifer.
Marty, don't go
this way.

06:57.117 --> 06:58.151
Strickland's
looking for you.

06:59.252 --> 06:59.953
If you get caught,
it'll be four tardies
in a row.

07:02.790 --> 07:04.958
All right, come on.
I think we're safe.

07:04.992 --> 07:07.127
You know, this time
it wasn't my fault.

07:07.160 --> 07:09.096
The doc set
all his clocks
25 minutes slow.

07:09.129 --> 07:11.231
Doc?

07:11.264 --> 07:14.001
Am I to understand you're
still hanging around with
Dr. Emmett Brown, McFly?

07:14.034 --> 07:15.803
(CLICKING TONGUE)

07:15.836 --> 07:18.872
Tardy slip for you,
Miss Parker.

07:18.906 --> 07:22.510
And one for you, McFly.
I believe that makes
four in a row.

07:22.743 --> 07:25.513
Let me give you
a nickel's worth of
free advice, young man.

07:25.746 --> 07:28.916
This so-called
Dr. Brown is dangerous.
He's a real nutcase.

07:28.949 --> 07:30.784
You hang around with him,
you're gonna end up
in big trouble.

07:30.818 --> 07:33.220
Ooh. Yes, sir.

07:33.253 --> 07:37.024
You got a real
attitude problem, McFly.
You're a slacker.

07:37.057 --> 07:38.258
You remind me
of your father
when he went here.

07:38.291 --> 07:40.994
He was a slacker, too.

07:41.028 --> 07:43.196
Can I go now,
Mr. Strickland?

07:43.230 --> 07:45.098
I noticed your band
is on the roster

07:45.132 --> 07:47.167
for the dance auditions
after school today.

07:47.200 --> 07:49.537
Why even bother, McFly?
You don't have a chance.

07:49.770 --> 07:51.505
You're too much
like your old man.

07:51.539 --> 07:53.807
No McFly ever amounted
to anything

07:53.841 --> 07:55.042
in the history
of Hill Valley.

07:57.845 --> 07:59.112
Yeah, well,
history is gonna change.

08:01.549 --> 08:02.816
Next, please.

08:04.552 --> 08:06.053
(SYNTHESIZER PLAYING)

08:08.822 --> 08:09.790
Okay, guys,
let's rock 'n roll.

08:12.125 --> 08:13.193
All right.

08:14.928 --> 08:16.930
We're the...
We're the Pinheads.

08:18.899 --> 08:20.267
One, two, three.

08:20.300 --> 08:22.035
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

08:40.187 --> 08:42.823
Okay, that's enough.
Thank you, fellas.

08:43.891 --> 08:45.993
Hold it, fellas.

08:46.026 --> 08:47.628
I'm afraid you're
just too darn loud.

08:48.662 --> 08:49.963
Next, please.

08:52.600 --> 08:54.301
Bring up
the next group, please.

08:57.304 --> 08:59.907
ANNOUNCER: Re-elect Mayor
"Goldie" Wilson.

08:59.940 --> 09:02.075
Progress is
his middle name.

09:02.109 --> 09:04.612
MARTY: "Too loud."
I can't believe it.

09:04.645 --> 09:07.114
I'm never gonna
get a chance to play
in front of anybody.

09:07.147 --> 09:09.316
Marty,
one rejection isn't
the end of the world.

09:09.349 --> 09:12.019
I just don't think
I'm cut out for music.

09:12.052 --> 09:14.021
But you're good, Marty.
You're really good,

09:14.054 --> 09:15.956
and this audition
tape of yours is great.

09:15.989 --> 09:18.225
You've gotta send it in
to the record company.

09:18.258 --> 09:19.927
It's like Doc's
always saying.
Yeah, I know. I know.

09:19.960 --> 09:20.994
"If you put
your mind to it,

09:21.028 --> 09:23.230
"you can
accomplish anything."

09:23.263 --> 09:25.365
That's good advice, Marty.

09:25.398 --> 09:27.200
All right,
okay, Jennifer.

09:27.234 --> 09:29.202
What if I send in the tape
and they don't like it?

09:29.236 --> 09:31.371
What if they say
I'm no good?

09:31.404 --> 09:33.674
What if they say,
"Get out of here, kid.
You got no future"?

09:33.907 --> 09:36.977
I mean, I just
don't think I can take
that kind of rejection.

09:37.010 --> 09:39.112
Jesus, I'm starting to
sound like my old man.

09:39.146 --> 09:41.081
Come on.
He's not that bad.
Save the clock tower.

09:41.114 --> 09:43.884
At least he's letting
you borrow the car
tomorrow night.

09:44.718 --> 09:46.286
Check out that 4x4.

09:47.187 --> 09:48.656
That is hot.

09:48.889 --> 09:50.190
Okay. Back her up.

09:50.223 --> 09:54.394
Someday, Jennifer.
Someday.

09:54.427 --> 09:57.064
Wouldn't it be great
to take that truck
up to the lake?

09:58.999 --> 10:01.068
Throw a couple of
sleeping bags
in the back.

10:03.036 --> 10:04.938
Lie out
underneath the stars.

10:04.972 --> 10:06.173
Stop it.
What?

10:07.675 --> 10:10.143
Does your mom know?
About tomorrow night?

10:10.177 --> 10:11.979
No, get out of town.

10:12.012 --> 10:14.281
My mom thinks
I'm going camping
with the guys.

10:14.314 --> 10:16.083
Jennifer, my mother
would freak out

10:16.116 --> 10:17.384
if she knew I was going
up there with you,

10:17.417 --> 10:20.087
and I'd get the
standard lecture about

10:20.120 --> 10:22.422
how she never
did that kind of stuff
when she was a kid.

10:22.455 --> 10:25.192
I mean, look,
I think the woman
was born a nun.

10:25.225 --> 10:27.961
She's just trying to
keep you respectable.

10:27.995 --> 10:29.697
Well, she's not doing
a very good job.

10:29.930 --> 10:31.331
Terrible.

10:31.364 --> 10:35.335
Save the clock tower.
Save the clock tower.

10:35.368 --> 10:39.339
Mayor Wilson is
sponsoring an initiative
to replace that clock.

10:39.372 --> 10:42.042
Thirty years ago,
lightning struck
that clock tower

10:42.075 --> 10:43.711
and the clock
hasn't run since.

10:43.944 --> 10:46.179
We at the Hill Valley
Preservation Society

10:46.213 --> 10:48.448
think it should be preserved
exactly the way it is

10:48.481 --> 10:50.283
as part of our history
and heritage.

10:50.317 --> 10:51.218
There you go, lady.
There's a quarter.

10:51.251 --> 10:52.452
Thank you.

10:52.485 --> 10:53.353
Don't forget
to take a flyer.

10:53.386 --> 10:54.454
Right.

10:54.487 --> 10:56.223
Save the clock tower!

10:58.191 --> 10:59.392
Where were we?

11:00.260 --> 11:01.695
Right about here.

11:01.729 --> 11:02.229
(CAR HORN HONKING)
MAN: Jennifer!

11:06.033 --> 11:08.135
It's my dad.
I've got to go.
Right.

11:08.168 --> 11:09.703
I'll call you tonight.

11:09.737 --> 11:11.138
I'll be at my grandma's.

11:11.171 --> 11:13.106
Here, let me
give you the number.

11:18.211 --> 11:19.112
Bye.

12:03.190 --> 12:06.059
RADIO DISPATCHER:
Bravo, Tango, Delta 6-2-9.

12:06.093 --> 12:08.395
Tow for impoundment.
Any unit, please respond.

12:11.298 --> 12:13.366
Perfect.
Just perfect.

12:17.838 --> 12:20.407
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

12:20.440 --> 12:22.843
I can't believe you'd
loan me your car

12:22.876 --> 12:24.812
without telling me
it had a blind spot.

12:24.845 --> 12:26.413
Blind spot?
I could've
been killed.

12:26.446 --> 12:29.282
Now, Biff, now,
I never noticed

12:29.316 --> 12:32.786
that the car had
any blind spot before
when I would drive it.

12:32.820 --> 12:34.554
Hi, Son.

12:34.587 --> 12:37.090
BIFF: What, are you blind,
McFly? It's there.

12:37.124 --> 12:38.525
How else do you explain
that wreck out there?

12:38.558 --> 12:42.429
GEORGE: Biff, can I assume

12:42.462 --> 12:45.298
that your insurance
is going to pay
for the damage?

12:45.332 --> 12:47.567
My insurance?
It's your car.

12:47.600 --> 12:49.169
Your insurance
should pay for it.

12:49.202 --> 12:51.138
I wanna know who's
going to pay for this?

12:51.171 --> 12:52.539
I spilled beer
all over it when the
car smashed into me.

12:52.572 --> 12:53.406
Who's gonna pay
my cleaning bill?

12:53.440 --> 12:54.875
GEORGE: Ah...

12:54.908 --> 12:56.844
BIFF: And where's
my reports?

12:57.077 --> 12:58.478
Well, I haven't
finished those up yet,

12:58.511 --> 13:01.248
but I figured since
they weren't due till...

13:01.281 --> 13:03.516
Hello? Hello?
Anybody home? Huh?

13:04.918 --> 13:07.387
Think, McFly. Think!
All right.

13:07.420 --> 13:09.422
I got to have time
to get them retyped.

13:09.456 --> 13:10.590
Do you realize
what would happen

13:10.623 --> 13:13.326
if I hand in my reports
in your handwriting?

13:13.360 --> 13:15.462
I'll get fired.

13:15.495 --> 13:18.198
You wouldn't want
that to happen,
would you?

13:18.231 --> 13:20.233
Would you?
Of course not, Biff.

13:20.267 --> 13:22.870
Now, I wouldn't
want that to happen.

13:23.103 --> 13:25.873
Now, look.
I'll finish those
reports on up tonight,

13:26.106 --> 13:28.575
and I'll run them on over
first thing tomorrow,
all right?

13:28.608 --> 13:30.310
Not too early.
I sleep in Saturday.

13:30.343 --> 13:31.444
McFly, your shoe's untied.

13:31.478 --> 13:32.612
(LAUGHING) Oh.

13:32.645 --> 13:35.482
Don't be so gullible, McFly.

13:35.515 --> 13:36.549
Got the place
fixed up nice,
though, McFly.

13:39.552 --> 13:41.521
I have your car towed
all the way to your house

13:41.554 --> 13:43.156
and all you got for me
is lite beer?

13:43.190 --> 13:44.257
(LAUGHS)

13:51.298 --> 13:53.266
What are you
looking at, butthead?

13:55.535 --> 13:57.270
Say hi to your mom
for me.

14:00.540 --> 14:02.642
I know what you're
going to say, Son,

14:02.675 --> 14:04.844
and you're right.
You're right.

14:06.513 --> 14:10.250
But Biff just happens
to be my supervisor,

14:10.283 --> 14:12.185
(CAR DRIVING AWAY)

14:12.219 --> 14:14.521
and I'm afraid I'm
just not very good
at confrontations.

14:15.956 --> 14:17.424
But the car, Dad.

14:19.659 --> 14:21.895
I mean, he wrecked it.
He totaled it.

14:23.496 --> 14:25.665
I needed that car
tomorrow night, Dad.

14:25.698 --> 14:27.434
Do you have any idea
how important
this was to me?

14:27.467 --> 14:28.969
Do you have any clue?

14:29.002 --> 14:31.171
I know, and all I can
say is, I'm...

14:31.604 --> 14:33.673
I'm sorry.

14:33.706 --> 14:36.409
Believe me, Marty,
you're better off

14:36.443 --> 14:39.379
without having to worry
about all the aggravation

14:39.412 --> 14:42.582
and headaches of
playing at that dance.

14:42.615 --> 14:44.417
DAVID: He's
absolutely right, Marty.

14:44.451 --> 14:46.419
The last thing you
need is headaches.

14:47.554 --> 14:48.688
(LAUGHING)

14:48.721 --> 14:49.957
(BOTH LAUGHING)

14:55.295 --> 14:58.999
Kids, we're going to
have to eat this cake
by ourselves.

14:59.032 --> 15:00.667
Your Uncle Joey didn't
make parole again.

15:02.002 --> 15:03.703
(LORRAINE SIGHS)

15:03.736 --> 15:07.307
I think it would
be nice if you all
dropped him a line.

15:07.340 --> 15:08.608
MARTY: Uncle
"Jailbird" Joey?

15:08.641 --> 15:10.710
He's your brother, Mom.

15:10.743 --> 15:14.948
Yeah. I think it's
a major embarrassment,
having an uncle in prison.

15:14.982 --> 15:16.516
We all make mistakes
in life, children.

15:16.549 --> 15:18.418
God damn it.
I'm late.

15:18.451 --> 15:20.620
David,
watch your mouth!

15:20.653 --> 15:23.256
You come here and
kiss your mother
before you go. Come here.

15:23.290 --> 15:25.492
Come on, Mom.
Make it fast.
I'll miss my bus.

15:26.359 --> 15:27.995
See you later, Pop.

15:28.228 --> 15:30.630
(EXCLAIMS) Time to
change that oil.

15:30.663 --> 15:31.999
(LAUGHING)

15:34.234 --> 15:37.604
Hey, Marty. I'm not
your answering service.

15:37.637 --> 15:40.040
While you were outside
pouting over the car,

15:40.073 --> 15:42.342
Jennifer Parker
called you twice.

15:42.375 --> 15:44.044
I don't like her, Marty.

15:44.077 --> 15:47.414
Any girl who calls up a boy
is just asking for trouble.

15:47.447 --> 15:50.050
Oh, Mother,
there's nothing wrong
with calling a boy.

15:50.283 --> 15:54.454
I think it's terrible.
Girls chasing boys.

15:54.487 --> 15:57.424
When I was your age,
I never chased a boy
or called a boy

15:57.457 --> 16:00.627
or sat in a parked car
with a boy.

16:00.660 --> 16:02.996
Then how am I supposed
to ever meet anybody?

16:04.264 --> 16:06.633
Well, it'll just happen.

16:06.666 --> 16:09.402
Like the way
I met your father.

16:09.436 --> 16:11.538
That was so stupid.
Grandpa hit him
with the car.

16:12.405 --> 16:13.673
It was meant to be.

16:15.308 --> 16:18.645
Anyway, if Grandpa
hadn't hit him,

16:18.678 --> 16:20.313
then none of you
would have been born.

16:20.347 --> 16:22.549
Yeah, well.

16:22.582 --> 16:24.051
I still don't understand
what Dad was doing

16:24.084 --> 16:25.718
in the middle
of the street.

16:25.752 --> 16:28.021
What was it, George?
Bird-watching?

16:28.055 --> 16:31.091
What, Lorraine? What?

16:31.124 --> 16:33.660
Anyway, your Grandpa
hit him with the car

16:33.693 --> 16:35.062
and brought him
into the house.

16:36.663 --> 16:38.098
He seemed so helpless,

16:42.135 --> 16:45.105
like a little lost puppy,
and my heart just
went out to him.

16:45.338 --> 16:47.707
LINDA: Yeah, Mom, we know.
You've told us this
story a million times.

16:47.740 --> 16:49.409
You felt sorry for him,

16:49.442 --> 16:50.810
so you decided
to go with him

16:50.843 --> 16:52.645
to the Fish Under
the Sea dance.

16:52.679 --> 16:55.348
No. It was the Enchantment
Under the Sea dance.

16:56.683 --> 17:00.687
Our first date.
I'll never forget it.

17:00.720 --> 17:02.655
It was the night of that
terrible thunderstorm,
remember, George?

17:02.689 --> 17:04.391
(INDISTINCT CHATTER ON TV)

17:06.726 --> 17:09.762
Your father kissed me
for the very first time
on that dance floor.

17:12.465 --> 17:14.767
It was then
that I realized

17:14.801 --> 17:17.137
that I was going to spend
the rest of my life with him.

17:17.170 --> 17:18.605
(LAUGHING)

17:28.181 --> 17:29.782
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

17:39.659 --> 17:41.161
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

17:45.898 --> 17:47.667
Hello.

17:47.700 --> 17:48.735
DOC: Marty, you didn't
fall asleep, did you?

17:48.768 --> 17:50.103
Doc.

17:51.504 --> 17:54.741
No. No, don't be silly.

17:54.774 --> 17:57.877
Listen,
this is very important.
I forgot my video camera.

17:57.910 --> 18:00.147
Can you stop by my place
and pick it up on
your way to the mall?

18:00.380 --> 18:02.649
Yeah. I'm on my way.

18:27.574 --> 18:29.509
Einstein! Hey, Einstein,
where's the doc, boy? Huh?

18:29.542 --> 18:30.443
(WHIMPERING)

18:31.478 --> 18:32.879
(MACHINE HUMMING)

18:35.582 --> 18:36.549
(GATE UNLOCKING)

19:10.583 --> 19:11.684
(ENGINE REVVING)

19:13.253 --> 19:14.454
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

19:24.531 --> 19:25.465
Doc!

19:26.866 --> 19:27.967
Marty! You made it!

19:28.000 --> 19:29.836
Yeah.

19:29.869 --> 19:31.838
Welcome to
my latest experiment.
This is the big one,

19:31.871 --> 19:33.706
the one I've been
waiting for all my life.

19:33.740 --> 19:35.708
Well, it's a DeLorean...

19:35.742 --> 19:37.244
Bear with me, Marty.
All your questions
will be answered.

19:37.277 --> 19:38.278
Roll tape
and we'll proceed.

19:38.311 --> 19:39.712
Doc,

19:39.746 --> 19:40.713
is that a DEVO suit?

19:40.747 --> 19:41.881
Never mind that now.

19:41.914 --> 19:43.283
Not now.

19:43.316 --> 19:44.984
All right. I'm ready.

19:45.017 --> 19:46.986
Good evening.
I'm Dr. Emmett Brown.

19:47.019 --> 19:49.289
I'm standing on
the parking lot
at Twin Pines Mall.

19:49.522 --> 19:52.825
It's Saturday morning,
October 26, 1985, 1:18 a.m.,

19:52.859 --> 19:55.228
and this is temporal
experiment number one.

19:55.262 --> 19:57.530
Come on, Einie.
Hey, hey, boy,
get in there.

19:57.564 --> 19:58.931
That a boy!
In you go. Sit down.

20:00.567 --> 20:01.601
Put your seat belt on.
That's it.

20:03.970 --> 20:04.971
(GRUNTING)

20:06.906 --> 20:07.807
Whoa, whoa. Whoa.

20:07.840 --> 20:09.208
Okay.

20:10.910 --> 20:13.880
Please note that
Einstein's clock

20:13.913 --> 20:16.716
is in precise synchronization
with my control watch.

20:16.749 --> 20:17.917
Got it?
Right. Check, Doc.

20:17.950 --> 20:18.851
Good.

20:21.754 --> 20:23.923
Have a good trip, Einstein.
Watch your head.

20:30.363 --> 20:31.298
You got that thing
hooked up to the car?

20:31.531 --> 20:32.632
(MACHINE HUMMING)

20:32.665 --> 20:33.666
Watch this.

20:33.700 --> 20:35.668
Yeah. Okay. Got it.

20:39.939 --> 20:40.873
Jesus!

20:46.045 --> 20:47.780
Not me!
The car! The car!

20:47.814 --> 20:48.981
(TIRES SQUEALING)

20:55.388 --> 20:56.689
(ENGINE REVVING)

21:05.365 --> 21:08.067
If my calculations
are correct,

21:08.100 --> 21:11.070
when this baby
hits 88 miles per hour

21:11.103 --> 21:12.639
you're going to see
some serious shit.

21:16.676 --> 21:17.710
(TIRES SCREECHING)

21:19.045 --> 21:19.979
(REMOTE CONTROL BEEPING)

21:31.858 --> 21:33.626
(RAPID BEEPING)

21:49.376 --> 21:50.643
Watch this.
Watch this.

22:07.794 --> 22:08.861
(LAUGHS)

22:08.895 --> 22:11.130
What did I tell you?

22:11.163 --> 22:14.634
88 miles per hour!

22:18.070 --> 22:19.839
The temporal
displacement occurred

22:19.872 --> 22:22.642
exactly 1:20 a.m.
and zero seconds!

22:24.644 --> 22:26.879
Jesus Christ!

22:26.913 --> 22:29.416
Jesus Christ, Doc!
You disintegrated Einstein!

22:29.649 --> 22:32.452
Calm down, Marty.
I didn't
disintegrate anything.

22:32.485 --> 22:36.756
The molecular structure of
both Einstein and the car
are completely intact.

22:36.789 --> 22:37.990
Then where the hell
are they?

22:38.024 --> 22:39.759
The appropriate
question is,

22:39.792 --> 22:41.761
"When the hell
are they?"

22:41.794 --> 22:46.433
You see, Einstein has
just become the world's
first time traveler.

22:46.466 --> 22:50.403
I sent him
into the future.

22:50.437 --> 22:52.472
One minute
into the future,
to be exact.

22:52.705 --> 22:55.908
At precisely 1:21 a.m.
and zero seconds,

22:55.942 --> 22:58.077
we shall catch up with him
and the time machine.

23:02.148 --> 23:03.816
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute, Doc.

23:06.052 --> 23:08.154
Are you telling me that
you built a time machine

23:09.822 --> 23:10.957
out of a DeLorean?

23:10.990 --> 23:12.892
The way I see it,

23:12.925 --> 23:14.427
if you're going to
build a time machine
into a car,

23:14.461 --> 23:16.863
why not do it
with some style?

23:16.896 --> 23:19.098
Besides, the stainless-steel
construction made the flux
dispersal...

23:19.131 --> 23:19.932
(WATCH BEEPING)

23:20.733 --> 23:21.901
Look out!

23:23.235 --> 23:24.837
(TIRES SCREECHING)

23:27.540 --> 23:28.708
(REMOTE CONTROL BEEPS)

23:55.868 --> 23:57.203
(TIME MACHINE CREAKING)

24:05.845 --> 24:06.979
(GASPS)

24:07.013 --> 24:08.180
What? Is it hot?

24:08.214 --> 24:09.782
It's cold. Damn cold.

24:12.251 --> 24:13.953
(DOC LAUGHING)

24:13.986 --> 24:15.555
Einstein,
you little devil!

24:15.788 --> 24:17.089
(CLOCK BEEPING)

24:18.190 --> 24:20.092
Einstein's clock is
exactly one minute

24:20.126 --> 24:22.028
behind mine
and still ticking!

24:24.797 --> 24:25.998
(BARKING)

24:26.032 --> 24:27.534
He's all right.
He's fine.

24:27.567 --> 24:29.969
And he's
completely unaware
that anything happened.

24:30.002 --> 24:32.972
As far as he's concerned,
the trip was instantaneous.

24:33.005 --> 24:35.041
That's why his watch
is exactly one minute
behind mine.

24:35.074 --> 24:36.275
He skipped over
that minute

24:36.308 --> 24:38.277
to instantly arrive
at this moment in time.

24:38.310 --> 24:39.979
Come here.
I'll show you
how it works.

24:40.012 --> 24:40.913
All right.

24:43.115 --> 24:45.552
First, you turn
the time circuits on.

24:45.785 --> 24:46.919
(MACHINE POWERING UP)

24:48.187 --> 24:49.922
(MACHINE WHIRS)

24:49.956 --> 24:51.157
This readout tells you
where you're going.

24:51.190 --> 24:52.525
This one tells you
where you are.

24:52.559 --> 24:54.193
This one tells you
where you were.

24:54.226 --> 24:56.529
You input your
destination time
on this keypad.

24:56.563 --> 24:57.897
Say you want to
see the signing

24:57.930 --> 25:00.066
of the Declaration
of Independence.

25:00.099 --> 25:02.201
(BEEPS)

25:02.234 --> 25:04.003
Or witness
the birth of Christ.

25:07.339 --> 25:09.876
Here's a red-letter date
in the history of science.

25:09.909 --> 25:12.178
November 5th, 1955.

25:16.649 --> 25:20.219
Yes, of course.
November 5th, 1955.

25:21.954 --> 25:23.055
What? I don't get it.
What happened?

25:23.089 --> 25:25.024
(LAUGHING)

25:25.057 --> 25:29.261
That was the day I
invented time travel.
I remember it vividly.

25:29.295 --> 25:31.130
I was standing on
the edge of my toilet,
hanging a clock.

25:31.163 --> 25:32.331
The porcelain was wet.
I slipped,

25:32.364 --> 25:34.033
hit my head on
the edge of the sink,

25:34.066 --> 25:36.335
and when I came to,
I had a revelation,

25:36.368 --> 25:40.873
a vision,
a picture in my head,
a picture of this.

25:40.907 --> 25:44.276
This is what makes
time travel possible.
The flux capacitor.

25:45.244 --> 25:47.113
Flux capacitor?

25:47.146 --> 25:49.248
It's taken me almost 30 years
and my entire family fortune

25:49.281 --> 25:51.951
to realize the vision
of that day.

25:51.984 --> 25:54.987
My God,
has it been that long?

25:55.021 --> 25:57.156
Things have certainly
changed around here.

25:58.925 --> 26:00.660
I remember when
this was all farmland

26:00.693 --> 26:02.194
as far as the eye
could see.

26:04.096 --> 26:05.998
Old man Peabody
owned all of this.

26:07.967 --> 26:10.870
He had this crazy idea
about breeding pine trees.

26:15.642 --> 26:19.278
This is heavy-duty, Doc.
This is great.

26:19.311 --> 26:22.048
Does it run on regular
unleaded gasoline?

26:22.081 --> 26:23.616
Unfortunately, no.
It requires something

26:23.650 --> 26:25.184
with a little more kick.
Plutonium.

26:26.085 --> 26:28.254
Plutonium.
Wait a minute.

26:28.287 --> 26:30.990
Are you telling me
that this sucker
is nuclear?

26:31.023 --> 26:32.692
Hey, hey, hey!
Keep rolling.
Keep rolling there.

26:32.925 --> 26:34.627
No, no, no,
this sucker's electrical,

26:34.661 --> 26:36.362
but I need
a nuclear reaction

26:36.395 --> 26:38.698
to generate
the 1.21 gigawatts
of electricity I need.

26:38.931 --> 26:41.634
Doc, you don't
just walk into a store
and buy plutonium.

26:42.401 --> 26:43.636
Did you rip that off?

26:46.673 --> 26:49.141
Of course.
From a group of
Libyan nationalists.

26:49.175 --> 26:50.910
They wanted me to
build them a bomb,

26:52.344 --> 26:52.979
so I took their plutonium
and, in turn, gave them
a shoddy bomb casing

26:53.813 --> 26:55.047
full of used
pinball machine parts.

26:56.148 --> 26:56.649
Come on. Let's get
you a radiation suit.
Jesus!

26:57.316 --> 26:57.684
We must prepare
to reload.

27:06.759 --> 27:08.060
(MUFFLED BREATHING)

27:09.061 --> 27:10.196
(AIR ESCAPING)

27:21.173 --> 27:22.174
(SUCKING)

27:27.379 --> 27:29.248
It's safe now.
Everything's lead-lined.

27:31.718 --> 27:33.753
Don't you lose
those tapes now.

27:33.986 --> 27:36.088
I need that
as a record.

27:36.122 --> 27:37.957
Let's put this back here.
There we go.

27:39.225 --> 27:40.392
(EXCLAIMS)

27:40.426 --> 27:43.095
I almost forgot
my luggage.

27:43.129 --> 27:45.231
Who knows if they've
got cotton underwear
in the future?

27:45.264 --> 27:46.332
I'm allergic to
all synthetics.

27:46.365 --> 27:47.967
The future?

27:49.235 --> 27:50.036
That's where
you're going?

27:51.103 --> 27:52.238
That's right,
25 years into the future.

27:53.605 --> 27:55.207
I've always dreamed
of seeing the future,
looking beyond my years,

27:55.241 --> 27:57.043
seeing the progress
of mankind.

27:57.076 --> 27:59.078
Why not?

27:59.111 --> 28:01.981
I'll also be able to
see who wins the next
25 World Series.

28:02.281 --> 28:03.449
Doc.

28:03.482 --> 28:05.184
Huh?

28:05.217 --> 28:07.119
Look me up when
you get there.

28:08.120 --> 28:10.256
Indeed, I will.
Roll 'em.

28:12.224 --> 28:13.726
(WHIRRING)

28:13.760 --> 28:15.127
(CLEARING THROAT)

28:17.096 --> 28:19.131
I, Dr. Emmett Brown,

28:21.300 --> 28:23.402
am about to embark on
an historic journey.

28:26.072 --> 28:27.506
(LAUGHING) What am
I thinking of?

28:27.539 --> 28:30.476
I almost forgot to
bring extra plutonium.

28:30.509 --> 28:32.478
How did I ever
expect to get back?
One pellet, one trip.

28:32.511 --> 28:34.246
I must be
out of my mind.

28:34.280 --> 28:35.414
(BARKING)

28:37.183 --> 28:38.450
What is it, Einie?

28:47.293 --> 28:49.328
Oh, my God.

28:49.361 --> 28:51.764
They found me.
I don't know how,
but they found me.

28:51.798 --> 28:52.799
Run for it, Marty!

28:53.032 --> 28:54.533
Who? Who?

28:54.566 --> 28:56.468
Who do you think?
The Libyans!

28:57.870 --> 28:59.138
(SHOUTING IN ARABIC)

28:59.171 --> 29:00.172
(TIRES SCREECHING)

29:00.206 --> 29:01.540
Holy shit!

29:01.573 --> 29:03.042
(GUN FIRING)

29:05.577 --> 29:07.279
I'll draw their fire!

29:15.454 --> 29:16.288
Doc, wait!

29:19.859 --> 29:20.793
(GUN COCKING)

29:31.170 --> 29:32.071
No!

29:33.405 --> 29:34.807
You bastard!

29:40.212 --> 29:41.247
(SHOUTING IN ARABIC)

29:45.417 --> 29:47.119
(GRUNTS)

29:47.153 --> 29:48.320
(GUN CLICKING)

29:48.354 --> 29:49.455
(SWEARING IN ARABIC)

29:51.557 --> 29:52.859
(GRUNTING)

29:54.093 --> 29:55.261
Go! Damn Soviet gun.

29:55.294 --> 29:56.295
(ENGINE STALLING)

30:01.233 --> 30:02.334
Go!

30:02.368 --> 30:03.235
(TIRES SCREECHING)

30:05.271 --> 30:06.505
(ENGINE STARTING)

30:17.516 --> 30:18.584
(BEEPING)

30:37.536 --> 30:39.138
(SHOUTING)

30:43.409 --> 30:45.277
Come on!
Move, damn it!

30:46.645 --> 30:47.947
Jesus!

31:08.300 --> 31:09.468
Holy shit!

31:10.702 --> 31:13.405
Let's see if you
bastards can do 90.

31:13.439 --> 31:14.640
(TIRES SQUEALING)

31:33.725 --> 31:35.227
(SCREAMING)

31:40.032 --> 31:41.333
(CRASHING)

31:43.302 --> 31:44.303
(CHICKENS CLUCKING)

31:47.339 --> 31:48.674
(DOG BARKING DISTANTLY)

31:50.642 --> 31:51.543
(DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

31:56.682 --> 31:57.950
(CAR BLINKER CLICKING)

32:05.424 --> 32:07.293
What is it?
What is it, Pa?

32:08.427 --> 32:12.298
Looks like an airplane
without wings.

32:12.331 --> 32:14.533
That ain't no airplane.
Look.

32:15.667 --> 32:17.269
(HYDRAULICS HISSING)

32:29.648 --> 32:30.682
(MUFFLED BREATHING)

32:32.518 --> 32:33.652
(SCREAMING)

32:35.754 --> 32:37.056
Children!

32:37.289 --> 32:37.990
Listen... Whoa.

32:42.061 --> 32:43.495
(COWS MOOING)

32:51.270 --> 32:52.304
Hello?

32:55.574 --> 32:56.642
Excuse me.

33:00.412 --> 33:01.613
Sorry about your barn.

33:01.647 --> 33:03.015
(GUN FIRING)

33:06.085 --> 33:08.420
It's already mutated
into human form!
Shoot it!

33:10.756 --> 33:12.591
Take that, you mutated
son of a bitch!

33:14.360 --> 33:15.527
(SCREAMING)

33:17.096 --> 33:18.030
BOY: Get away!

33:19.565 --> 33:21.067
MAN: Hold it.

33:21.100 --> 33:22.401
BOY: Shoot it, Pa!

33:24.836 --> 33:27.706
My pine! Why you...

33:30.576 --> 33:33.379
You space bastard!
You killed our pine!

33:36.582 --> 33:38.350
(TIRES SCREECHING)

33:38.384 --> 33:40.352
All right. All right.
Okay, McFly.

33:40.386 --> 33:42.421
Get a grip on yourself.
It's all a dream.

33:42.454 --> 33:44.823
It's just
a very intense dream.

33:44.856 --> 33:46.058
(PANTING)

33:47.459 --> 33:48.394
(BRAKES SQUEALING)

34:28.434 --> 34:29.635
Listen,
you got to help me.

34:29.668 --> 34:31.570
Don't stop,
Wilbur! Don't!

34:33.772 --> 34:34.606
It can't be.

34:36.708 --> 34:37.709
(MACHINE BEEPS)

34:41.447 --> 34:41.880
This is nuts.

34:44.183 --> 34:45.551
(ENGINE STALLING)

34:46.852 --> 34:48.120
Come on.

34:49.388 --> 34:50.756
Perfect.

34:50.789 --> 34:51.857
(MACHINE BEEPING INSISTENTLY)

35:21.553 --> 35:23.121
(MUSIC PLAYING)

35:42.674 --> 35:43.909
(HORN HONKING)

35:53.819 --> 35:54.520
(BELL DINGS)

35:56.755 --> 35:58.524
(GAS ATTENDANTS CHATTERING)

36:13.004 --> 36:14.473
(BOY COUNTING)

36:27.986 --> 36:29.621
(BELL TOLLING)

36:46.838 --> 36:50.309
ANNOUNCER:
Remember, fellow citizens,
the future is in your hands.

36:50.342 --> 36:53.712
If you believe in progress,
re-elect Mayor Red Thomas.

36:53.745 --> 36:56.014
Progress is
his middle name.

36:56.047 --> 36:58.784
Mayor Red Thomas'
progress platform

36:58.817 --> 37:01.287
means more jobs,
better education,

37:01.320 --> 37:04.823
bigger civic improvements
and lower taxes.

37:04.856 --> 37:07.993
On election day,
cast your vote
for a proven leader.

37:08.026 --> 37:09.928
Re-elect Mayor Red Thomas.

37:13.732 --> 37:15.567
This has got to
be a dream.

37:24.710 --> 37:26.678
(MUSIC PLAYING ON JUKEBOX)

37:32.818 --> 37:35.621
LOU: Hey, kid.
What'd you do? Jump ship?

37:35.654 --> 37:36.822
What?

37:36.855 --> 37:37.989
What's with
the life preserver?

37:43.695 --> 37:45.764
I just want to
use the phone.

37:45.797 --> 37:46.698
Yeah, it's in the back.

37:49.835 --> 37:50.836
MARTY: Brown.

37:53.705 --> 37:54.906
Great. You're alive.

37:54.940 --> 37:56.041
(PHONE RINGING)

37:58.109 --> 37:59.311
(WATCH BEEPING)

38:04.783 --> 38:05.717
(SIGHS)

38:06.885 --> 38:07.919
Come on.

38:15.927 --> 38:17.929
Do you know where
1640 Riverside...

38:17.963 --> 38:19.931
Are you going to
order something, kid?

38:21.933 --> 38:23.935
Yeah. Give me a Tab.

38:25.671 --> 38:27.873
Tab? I can't give you a tab
unless you order something.

38:27.906 --> 38:29.975
Right.
Give me a Pepsi Free.

38:30.008 --> 38:33.011
You want a Pepsi, pal,
you're going to pay for it.

38:33.044 --> 38:35.981
Just give me something
without any sugar in it,
okay?

38:36.014 --> 38:37.716
Something without sugar.

38:43.989 --> 38:45.123
(DOOR OPENS)

38:45.156 --> 38:46.625
BIFF: Hey, McFly.

38:49.428 --> 38:51.730
What do you think
you're doing?

38:51.763 --> 38:53.131
Biff.

38:53.164 --> 38:56.001
I'm talking to you, McFly,
you Irish bug!

38:56.034 --> 38:58.069
Hey, Biff. Hey, guys.
How are you doing?

38:58.103 --> 39:01.006
You got my homework
finished, McFly?

39:01.039 --> 39:03.108
Well, actually,
I figured since it
wasn't due till Monday...

39:03.141 --> 39:04.943
Hello? Hello?
Anybody home?

39:04.976 --> 39:06.878
(BOYS LAUGHING)

39:06.912 --> 39:08.747
Think, McFly. Think!
(LAUGHING) Okay.

39:08.780 --> 39:10.716
I got to have time
to recopy it.

39:10.749 --> 39:11.950
You realize
what would happen

39:11.983 --> 39:14.420
if I hand in my homework
in your handwriting?

39:14.653 --> 39:16.388
I'll get kicked
out of school.

39:16.422 --> 39:18.089
You wouldn't want that
to happen, would you?

39:20.191 --> 39:21.460
Would you?

39:21.693 --> 39:22.894
Now, of course not,
Biff.

39:22.928 --> 39:24.796
No.
I wouldn't want
that to happen.

39:24.830 --> 39:26.698
What are you
looking at, butthead?

39:26.732 --> 39:28.900
Biff, get a load of
this guy's life preserver.

39:28.934 --> 39:30.736
Dork thinks he's
going to drown.

39:30.769 --> 39:33.905
How about
my homework, McFly?

39:33.939 --> 39:37.409
Okay, Biff.
Well, I'll finish
that on up tonight

39:37.443 --> 39:40.178
and then I'll bring it
over first thing
tomorrow morning.

39:40.211 --> 39:41.947
Not too early.
I sleep in Sundays.

39:41.980 --> 39:43.114
Oh, McFly,
your shoe's untied!

39:43.148 --> 39:44.916
(BOYS LAUGHING)

39:44.950 --> 39:46.885
Don't be
so gullible, McFly.
Okay.

39:46.918 --> 39:47.953
I don't want to see
you in here again.

39:47.986 --> 39:50.055
Okay. All right.
Bye-bye.

40:11.977 --> 40:13.178
What?

40:13.211 --> 40:14.145
You're George McFly.

40:15.046 --> 40:16.848
Yeah. Who are you?

40:16.882 --> 40:18.450
Say! Why do you
let those boys

40:18.484 --> 40:19.951
push you around
like that for?

40:19.985 --> 40:21.853
Well, they're
bigger than me.

40:21.887 --> 40:24.490
Stand tall, boy.
Have some respect
for yourself.

40:24.523 --> 40:26.525
Don't you know,
if you let people
walk over you now,

40:26.758 --> 40:28.494
they'll be walking over you
for the rest of your life.

40:28.727 --> 40:30.228
Look at me.
You think I'm gonna

40:30.261 --> 40:31.930
spend the rest of my life
in this slop house?

40:31.963 --> 40:33.965
LOU: Watch it, Goldie.
No, sir!

40:33.999 --> 40:35.066
I'm gonna make
something of myself.

40:35.100 --> 40:36.468
I'm going
to night school,

40:36.502 --> 40:38.504
and one day,
I'm going to be somebody.

40:38.737 --> 40:40.238
That's right.
He's going to be mayor.

40:40.271 --> 40:41.473
Yeah, I'm...

40:42.207 --> 40:43.141
Mayor!

40:44.876 --> 40:48.847
Now that's a good idea!
I could run for mayor.

40:48.880 --> 40:50.816
A colored mayor.
That'll be the day.

40:50.849 --> 40:53.118
You wait and see,
Mr. Caruthers.
I will be mayor.

40:53.151 --> 40:55.053
I'll be the most
powerful man
in Hill Valley,

40:55.086 --> 40:57.055
and I'm going to
clean up this town.

40:57.088 --> 40:59.491
Good. You can start
by sweeping the floor.

41:02.861 --> 41:06.097
Mayor Goldie Wilson.
I like the sound of that.

41:10.068 --> 41:11.169
(BICYCLE BELL RINGS)

41:19.177 --> 41:22.047
Hey, Dad! George!
Hey, you on the bike!

41:53.912 --> 41:55.513
He's a peeping Tom.

41:59.951 --> 42:01.186
(GRUNTING)

42:01.219 --> 42:02.253
Dad!

42:02.287 --> 42:03.622
(HORN HONKING)

42:03.855 --> 42:04.255
(TIRES SCREECHING)

42:05.323 --> 42:06.825
(DOGS BARKING)

42:15.066 --> 42:17.002
Hey, wait a minute.
Wait a minute.
Who are you?

42:19.370 --> 42:22.173
Stella! Another one
of these damn kids

42:22.207 --> 42:23.208
jumped in front
of my car!

42:25.076 --> 42:27.312
Come on out here!
Help me take him
in the house!

42:31.116 --> 42:32.117
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

42:32.884 --> 42:35.020
Mom? That you?

42:36.387 --> 42:39.090
LORRAINE: There,
there, now. Just relax.

42:42.260 --> 42:44.863
You've been asleep for
almost nine hours now.

42:46.998 --> 42:49.034
I had a horrible nightmare.

42:50.936 --> 42:54.606
I dreamed that
I went back in time.
It was terrible.

42:56.007 --> 42:58.209
Well,

42:58.243 --> 43:01.079
you're safe and sound now,
back in good old 1955.

43:02.280 --> 43:03.615
1955?

43:07.418 --> 43:08.687
(MARTY GASPS)

43:08.720 --> 43:11.657
You're my...
You're my...

43:11.690 --> 43:12.323
My name is Lorraine.

43:14.159 --> 43:15.260
Lorraine Baines.

43:15.293 --> 43:16.194
Yeah.

43:17.929 --> 43:20.065
But you're...
You're so...

43:20.932 --> 43:25.036
You're so thin!

43:25.070 --> 43:27.305
Just relax, Calvin.
You got a big bruise
on your head.

43:30.208 --> 43:31.710
(EXCLAIMS)

43:31.943 --> 43:34.179
Where are my pants?

43:34.212 --> 43:36.682
Over there,
on my hope chest.

43:39.450 --> 43:41.186
I've never seen
purple underwear before,
Calvin.

43:42.453 --> 43:45.957
Calvin? Why do you
keep calling me Calvin?

43:45.991 --> 43:49.027
Well, that is
your name, isn't it?
Calvin Klein?

43:49.060 --> 43:51.963
It's written all over
your underwear.

43:51.997 --> 43:54.966
Oh, I guess they
call you Cal, huh?

43:55.000 --> 43:57.969
No, actually,
people call me Marty.

43:58.336 --> 43:59.270
Oh.

44:00.338 --> 44:02.307
Pleased to
meet you, Calvin.

44:03.341 --> 44:04.676
Marty.

44:06.244 --> 44:07.746
Klein.

44:07.779 --> 44:09.247
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

44:14.485 --> 44:16.254
Do you mind
if I sit here?

44:16.287 --> 44:17.756
No. Fine.

44:17.789 --> 44:19.958
No. Good.
Fine. Good.

44:22.360 --> 44:24.329
That's a big bruise
you have there.

44:24.362 --> 44:26.364
(SHOUTS)

44:26.397 --> 44:28.466
STELLA: Lorraine,
are you up there?

44:28.499 --> 44:30.736
Oh, my God!
It's my mother!

44:30.769 --> 44:33.238
Quick!
Put your pants back on!

44:42.280 --> 44:44.482
STELLA: So, tell me, Marty,
how long have you
been in port?

44:44.515 --> 44:46.084
MARTY: Excuse me?

44:46.117 --> 44:47.018
I guessed
you're a sailor.

44:48.153 --> 44:49.120
That's why you wear
that life preserver.

44:49.154 --> 44:50.789
Coast Guard.

44:50.822 --> 44:53.058
Sam, here's
the young man

44:53.091 --> 44:54.259
you hit with your car
out there.

44:54.292 --> 44:55.994
He's all right.
Thank God.

44:57.262 --> 44:57.996
What were you doing in
the middle of the street,
a kid your age?

44:59.097 --> 44:59.998
Don't pay attention to him.
He's in one of his moods.

45:00.899 --> 45:01.399
Sam, you quit fiddling
with that thing.

45:02.100 --> 45:03.101
Come in here
to dinner.

45:04.035 --> 45:05.203
Now, let's see.
You already know Lorraine.

45:06.204 --> 45:09.240
This is Milton,
this is Sally,
that's Toby,

45:09.274 --> 45:11.743
and over there
in the playpen
is little baby Joey.

45:13.779 --> 45:15.346
So, you're my uncle Joey.

45:17.148 --> 45:19.317
Better get used
to these bars, kid.

45:19.350 --> 45:24.122
Yes. Joey just loves
being in his playpen.

45:24.155 --> 45:25.323
He cries whenever
we take him out,

45:25.356 --> 45:27.325
so we just leave him
in there all the time.

45:27.358 --> 45:29.761
Well, Marty, I hope
you like meatloaf.

45:29.795 --> 45:31.763
Listen,
I really ought to...

45:31.797 --> 45:33.799
Sit here, Marty.

45:33.832 --> 45:35.801
Sam, stop fiddling
with that thing

45:35.834 --> 45:38.103
and come in here
and eat your dinner.

45:38.136 --> 45:39.838
(SAM CHORTLING)

45:40.071 --> 45:41.840
Look at it roll.
(EXCLAIMS)

45:41.873 --> 45:43.441
Now we can
watch Jackie Gleason
while we eat.

45:43.474 --> 45:45.143
(LAUGHING)

45:45.176 --> 45:46.411
(CHATTERING ON TV)

45:53.051 --> 45:54.485
It's our first
television set.

45:54.519 --> 45:55.787
Dad just
picked it up today.

45:57.288 --> 45:59.490
Do you have
a television?

45:59.524 --> 46:02.160
Well, yeah. You know
we have two of them.

46:02.193 --> 46:05.263
Wow! You must be rich.

46:05.296 --> 46:06.798
Oh, honey,
he's teasing you.

46:06.832 --> 46:09.100
Nobody has two
television sets.

46:09.134 --> 46:10.068
(CHUCKLES)

46:14.239 --> 46:16.507
Hey. Hey,
I've seen this one.

46:16.541 --> 46:18.543
I've seen this one!
This is a classic.

46:18.576 --> 46:21.847
This is where
Ralph dresses up
as a man from space.

46:21.880 --> 46:25.250
What do you mean,
you've seen this?
It's brand-new.

46:25.283 --> 46:26.885
Yeah, well,
I saw it on a rerun.

46:27.919 --> 46:29.855
What's a rerun?

46:29.888 --> 46:32.157
You'll find out.

46:32.190 --> 46:35.326
You know, Marty,
you look so familiar to me.
Do I know your mother?

46:37.328 --> 46:39.464
Yeah, I think
maybe you do.

46:39.497 --> 46:41.199
STELLA: Oh, then I want
to give her a call.

46:41.232 --> 46:42.433
I don't want her
to worry about you.

46:42.467 --> 46:43.568
You can't.

46:45.270 --> 46:47.873
(STUTTERING) That is,
nobody's home.

46:49.307 --> 46:50.275
Oh.

46:50.641 --> 46:51.576
Yet.

46:52.377 --> 46:54.545
Oh.

46:54.579 --> 46:58.416
Listen, do you know
where Riverside Drive is?

46:58.449 --> 46:59.885
It's on the other
end of town.

47:00.118 --> 47:02.487
A block past Maple.
East end of town.

47:02.520 --> 47:04.155
Wait a minute,
a block past Maple.

47:04.189 --> 47:06.191
That's John F.
Kennedy Drive.

47:07.392 --> 47:09.360
Who the hell
is John F. Kennedy?

47:09.394 --> 47:11.529
LORRAINE: Mother?

47:11.562 --> 47:14.632
With Marty's parents
out of town,

47:14.665 --> 47:17.402
don't you think he ought
to spend the night?

47:17.435 --> 47:19.504
I mean, after all,
Dad almost killed him
with the car.

47:19.537 --> 47:21.940
That's true, Marty.

47:21.973 --> 47:23.508
I think maybe you
should spend the night.

47:23.541 --> 47:24.943
I think you're
our responsibility.

47:24.976 --> 47:26.945
Gee, I don't know.

47:26.978 --> 47:28.246
And he can sleep
in my room.

47:29.280 --> 47:31.449
I gotta go!
I gotta go!

47:31.482 --> 47:32.918
Thanks very much.
It was wonderful.

47:33.151 --> 47:36.587
You were all great.
See you all later.
Much later.

47:41.559 --> 47:44.295
He's a very
strange young man.

47:44.329 --> 47:46.397
He's an idiot.

47:46.431 --> 47:49.968
Comes from upbringing.
His parents are
probably idiots, too.

47:50.001 --> 47:51.402
Lorraine,
you ever have a kid

47:51.436 --> 47:53.271
who acts that way,
I'll disown you.

48:31.476 --> 48:32.377
Doc?

48:33.478 --> 48:35.246
Don't say a word.

48:35.280 --> 48:36.447
(ELECTRONIC WARBLING)

48:36.481 --> 48:38.016
I don't wanna
know your name.

48:38.049 --> 48:38.716
I don't want to know
anything about you.

48:38.749 --> 48:40.952
Listen, Doc...
Quiet!

48:40.986 --> 48:42.487
Doc, it's me, Marty.
Don't tell me anything.

48:42.520 --> 48:44.589
Doc, you got to help...
Quiet. Quiet.

48:44.622 --> 48:45.991
(ELECTRONIC WARBLING)

48:47.392 --> 48:49.660
I'm going to
read your thoughts.

48:49.694 --> 48:52.730
Let's see now.
You've come here
from a great distance?

48:52.763 --> 48:53.999
Yeah. Exactly.

48:54.232 --> 48:55.000
Don't tell me!

48:56.267 --> 48:57.502
You want me to
buy a subscription

48:57.535 --> 48:58.603
to the
Saturday Evening Post.

48:58.636 --> 49:00.038
No.

49:00.071 --> 49:01.406
Not a word.
Not a word now!

49:01.439 --> 49:02.407
Quiet.

49:05.276 --> 49:08.613
Donations. You want me
to make a donation

49:08.646 --> 49:10.481
to the Coast Guard
Youth Auxiliary.

49:11.382 --> 49:12.483
Doc.

49:14.419 --> 49:15.520
I'm from the future.

49:15.553 --> 49:16.654
(ELECTRONIC WARBLING STOPS)

49:17.688 --> 49:20.491
I came here
in a time machine
that you invented.

49:20.525 --> 49:24.495
Now, I need
your help to get back
to the year 1985.

49:26.297 --> 49:27.498
My God.

49:32.503 --> 49:34.272
Do you know
what this means?

49:36.674 --> 49:40.778
It means
that this damn thing
doesn't work at all!

49:40.811 --> 49:42.580
Doc, you got to help me.
You are the only one

49:42.613 --> 49:45.383
who knows how your
time machine works.

49:45.416 --> 49:48.453
Time machine?
I haven't invented
any time machine.

49:50.821 --> 49:53.658
Okay. All right,
I'll prove it to you.

49:53.691 --> 49:56.727
Look at
my driver's license.
Expires 1987.

49:56.761 --> 49:58.063
Look at my birthday,
for crying out loud!

49:58.296 --> 50:00.398
I haven't even
been born yet.

50:00.431 --> 50:02.667
And look
at this picture.

50:02.700 --> 50:05.070
It's my brother,
my sister and me.

50:05.103 --> 50:07.572
Look at her sweatshirt, Doc.
"Class of 1984"?

50:09.140 --> 50:11.076
Pretty mediocre
photographic fakery.

50:11.309 --> 50:14.045
They cut off
your brother's hair.

50:14.079 --> 50:16.347
I'm telling the truth, Doc.
You got to believe me.

50:16.381 --> 50:18.349
Then tell me,
future boy,

50:18.383 --> 50:19.717
(LAUGHING)

50:19.750 --> 50:23.554
who's President of
the United States
in 1985?

50:23.588 --> 50:24.722
Ronald Reagan.

50:24.755 --> 50:27.125
Ronald Reagan?
The actor?

50:27.358 --> 50:28.793
(EXCLAIMS)

50:28.826 --> 50:30.795
Then who's vice president?
Jerry Lewis?

50:32.730 --> 50:34.699
I suppose Jane Wyman
is the First Lady.

50:34.732 --> 50:36.434
Whoa. Wait, Doc!

50:36.467 --> 50:38.503
And Jack Benny is
secretary of the treasury.

50:38.536 --> 50:40.538
Doc, you gotta
listen to me.

50:40.571 --> 50:42.373
I've had enough
practical jokes
for one evening.

50:42.407 --> 50:43.141
Good night,
future boy!

50:43.374 --> 50:45.076
No, wait, Doc. Doc.

50:45.110 --> 50:47.712
The bruise on your head,
I know how that happened.

50:47.745 --> 50:49.114
You told me
the whole story.

50:49.347 --> 50:50.681
You were standing
on your toilet

50:50.715 --> 50:51.682
and you were
hanging a clock,

50:52.683 --> 50:54.719
and you fell
and you hit your
head on the sink.

50:54.752 --> 50:57.488
That's when you came up
with the idea for
the flux capacitor,

50:57.522 --> 51:01.126
which is what makes
time travel possible.

51:01.159 --> 51:02.160
(DOOR UNLOCKING)

51:14.705 --> 51:18.075
There's something wrong
with the starter,
so I hid it here.

51:29.187 --> 51:32.457
After I fell
off my toilet,
I drew this.

51:37.228 --> 51:38.663
The flux capacitor.

51:47.605 --> 51:49.140
(ELECTRIC CRACKLING)

51:56.681 --> 51:57.748
It works!

51:58.583 --> 52:00.585
(DOC LAUGHING)

52:00.618 --> 52:01.819
It works!

52:03.721 --> 52:05.823
I finally invent
something that works!

52:07.258 --> 52:10.528
You bet your ass
it works.

52:10.561 --> 52:13.198
Somehow we've got
to sneak this back
to my laboratory.

52:13.231 --> 52:14.732
We've got to
get you home!

52:15.733 --> 52:17.235
Okay, Doc, this is it.

52:19.770 --> 52:21.739
Never mind that.
Never mind that now.

52:21.772 --> 52:25.243
Why, that's me!
Look at me!
I'm an old man.

52:25.276 --> 52:26.811
Good evening.
I'm Dr. Emmett Brown.

52:28.313 --> 52:28.346
I'm standing on
the parking lot
at Twin Pines Mall.

52:29.113 --> 52:30.681
Thank God,
I've still got my hair.

52:31.582 --> 52:32.683
What's on Earth is
this thing I'm wearing?

52:32.717 --> 52:34.752
This is a radiation suit.

52:34.785 --> 52:37.488
Radiation suit?

52:37.522 --> 52:39.690
Of course.
'Cause of all the fallout
from the atomic wars.

52:39.724 --> 52:40.925
(VIDEO REWINDING)

52:40.958 --> 52:44.495
This is truly amazing.

52:44.529 --> 52:47.665
A portable
television studio.

52:47.698 --> 52:48.966
No wonder your president
has to be an actor.

52:48.999 --> 52:51.536
He's gotta look good
on television.

52:51.569 --> 52:53.170
Whoa. This is it.
This is the part
coming up, Doc.

52:54.505 --> 52:55.806
No, no, no,
this sucker's electrical,

52:55.840 --> 52:57.174
but I need
a nuclear reaction

52:58.209 --> 52:58.743
to generate
the 1.21 gigawatts...

52:59.310 --> 53:00.245
What did I just say?

53:01.612 --> 53:02.813
(VIDEO REWINDING)

53:04.715 --> 53:05.516
This sucker's electrical,

53:06.584 --> 53:06.884
but I need
a nuclear reaction

53:07.852 --> 53:08.253
to generate
the 1.21 gigawatts...

53:09.019 --> 53:10.721
1.21 gigawatts!

53:12.590 --> 53:14.525
1.21 gigawatts.

53:16.761 --> 53:17.928
Great Scott!

53:20.731 --> 53:24.302
What the hell
is a gigawatt?

53:24.335 --> 53:28.673
How could I have
been so careless?
1.21 gigawatts!

53:28.706 --> 53:30.841
Tom, how am I
going to generate
that kind of power?

53:30.875 --> 53:32.743
It can't be done,
can it?

53:32.777 --> 53:34.945
Doc, look. All we need
is a little plutonium.

53:34.979 --> 53:36.281
(EXCLAIMS)

53:36.514 --> 53:38.649
I'm sure that in 1985,

53:38.683 --> 53:40.818
plutonium is available
in every corner drugstore,

53:40.851 --> 53:43.754
but in 1955,
it's a little hard
to come by.

53:43.788 --> 53:46.791
Marty, I'm sorry,
but I'm afraid
you're stuck here.

53:46.824 --> 53:48.259
Whoa, whoa.

53:49.560 --> 53:52.330
Doc, stuck here?
I can't be stuck here.
I got a life in 1985.

53:52.563 --> 53:53.631
I got a girl.

53:53.664 --> 53:55.633
Is she pretty?

53:55.666 --> 53:59.937
Doc, she's beautiful.
She's crazy about me.

53:59.970 --> 54:03.274
Look at this. Look
what she wrote here, Doc.
I mean, that says it all.

54:04.875 --> 54:08.713
Doc, you're my only hope.

54:08.746 --> 54:11.916
Marty, I'm sorry,
but the only power source
capable of generating

54:11.949 --> 54:14.685
1.21 gigawatts
of electricity
is a bolt of lightning.

54:16.020 --> 54:17.322
What did you say?

54:17.355 --> 54:18.789
A bolt of lightning.

54:18.823 --> 54:19.690
Unfortunately,
you never know

54:20.591 --> 54:22.627
when or where it's
ever going to strike.

54:24.094 --> 54:25.563
We do now.

54:30.968 --> 54:33.971
This is it!
This is the answer.

54:35.105 --> 54:37.808
It says here that
a bolt of lightning

54:37.842 --> 54:38.843
is going to
strike the clock tower

54:39.777 --> 54:41.712
at precisely 10:04 p.m.
next Saturday night!

54:45.783 --> 54:48.719
If we could somehow
harness this lightning,

54:50.655 --> 54:52.990
channel it into
the flux capacitor,

54:54.725 --> 54:57.628
it just might work.

54:57.662 --> 55:00.731
Next Saturday night,
we're sending you
back to the future!

55:02.600 --> 55:04.001
Okay, all right.
Saturday's good.
Saturday's good.

55:04.034 --> 55:06.003
I can spend
a week in 1955.

55:06.036 --> 55:07.972
I can hang out.
You can show me around.

55:08.005 --> 55:09.807
Marty, that is completely
out of the question.

55:09.840 --> 55:11.376
You must not
leave this house.

55:11.609 --> 55:13.878
You must not see anybody
or talk to anybody.

55:13.911 --> 55:15.713
Anything you do can have
serious repercussions
on future events.

55:15.746 --> 55:17.047
Do you understand?

55:18.148 --> 55:19.950
Yeah. Sure. Okay.

55:20.851 --> 55:23.354
Marty,

55:23.388 --> 55:25.756
have you interacted
with anybody else today,
besides me?

55:28.158 --> 55:30.961
Yeah, well,
I might've sort of
bumped into my parents.

55:30.995 --> 55:33.097
Great Scott!

55:33.130 --> 55:34.732
Let me see
that photograph again
of your brother.

55:38.903 --> 55:41.439
Just as I thought.
This proves my theory.
Look at your brother.

55:43.408 --> 55:45.910
MARTY: His head's gone.
It's like it's been erased.

55:47.978 --> 55:49.747
Erased from existence.

55:54.184 --> 55:56.020
Whoa.

55:56.053 --> 55:58.456
They really
cleaned this place up.
Looks brand-new.

55:58.489 --> 55:59.790
DOC: Now remember.

55:59.824 --> 56:01.025
According to my theory,
you interfered

56:01.058 --> 56:02.760
with your parents'
first meeting.

56:02.793 --> 56:03.894
If they don't meet,
they won't fall in love,

56:04.962 --> 56:05.430
they won't get married
and they won't have kids.

56:06.163 --> 56:06.797
That's why your
older brother's

56:07.632 --> 56:08.666
disappearing from
that photograph.

56:10.000 --> 56:10.034
Your sister will follow,
and unless you repair
the damage,

56:10.501 --> 56:11.869
you'll be next.

56:13.103 --> 56:13.137
MARTY: Sounds pretty heavy.
Weight has nothing
to do with it.

56:13.571 --> 56:14.439
(BELL RINGING)

56:15.005 --> 56:16.006
Which one's your pop?

56:17.508 --> 56:18.676
That's him.

56:19.209 --> 56:21.912
Okay.
Okay, you guys.

56:21.946 --> 56:23.781
(LAUGHING SARCASTICALLY)

56:23.814 --> 56:26.784
Very funny. You guys
are being real mature.

56:26.817 --> 56:28.786
Maybe you were adopted.

56:28.819 --> 56:30.955
Okay, real mature, guys.

56:32.122 --> 56:33.491
Okay, pick up my books.

56:33.524 --> 56:34.759
McFly.

56:34.792 --> 56:37.061
That's Strickland.

56:37.094 --> 56:39.430
Jesus, didn't that guy
ever have hair?

56:39.464 --> 56:42.199
Shape up, man.
You're a slacker.

56:42.232 --> 56:44.902
Do you want to
be a slacker for
the rest of your life?

56:44.935 --> 56:46.871
No.

56:46.904 --> 56:48.005
What did your mother
ever see in that kid?

56:48.038 --> 56:49.740
I don't know, Doc.

56:49.774 --> 56:51.509
I guess she felt
sorry for him

56:51.542 --> 56:53.911
'cause her dad hit him
with the car.

56:53.944 --> 56:56.447
Hit me with the car.

56:56.481 --> 56:59.116
That's the Florence
Nightingale effect.

56:59.149 --> 57:01.752
It happens in hospitals
when nurses fall in love
with their patients.

57:01.786 --> 57:02.787
Go to it, kid.

57:03.854 --> 57:07.458
Hey, George, buddy.

57:07.492 --> 57:10.528
I have been looking
all over for you.

57:10.561 --> 57:12.763
You remember me,
the guy who saved
your life the other day?

57:12.797 --> 57:13.898
Oh.

57:13.931 --> 57:15.132
Yeah.
Good.

57:15.165 --> 57:16.801
There's somebody
I'd like you to meet.

57:21.205 --> 57:23.007
Lorraine?

57:23.040 --> 57:23.941
Calvin!

57:26.110 --> 57:28.813
I'd like you to
meet my good friend
George McFly.

57:28.846 --> 57:31.482
Hi. It's really
a pleasure to meet you.

57:32.917 --> 57:33.984
How's your head?

57:34.018 --> 57:35.886
Good. Fine.

57:35.920 --> 57:37.855
Oh. I've been so
worried about you

57:37.888 --> 57:39.557
ever since you ran off
the other night.

57:39.590 --> 57:40.858
Are you okay?
Yeah.

57:40.891 --> 57:42.092
(BELL RINGING)

57:42.126 --> 57:43.260
I'm sorry.
I have to go.

57:43.293 --> 57:44.461
Come on!

57:45.596 --> 57:47.031
Isn't he a dreamboat?

57:51.802 --> 57:53.538
Doc, she didn't
even look at him.

57:53.771 --> 57:54.939
This is more serious
than I thought.

57:54.972 --> 57:56.874
Apparently, your mother
is amorously infatuated
with you,

57:56.907 --> 57:58.108
instead of your father.

57:59.143 --> 58:00.911
Whoa. Wait a minute, Doc.

58:02.179 --> 58:03.948
Are you trying to tell me
that my mother has
got the hots for me?

58:03.981 --> 58:05.215
Precisely.

58:05.249 --> 58:07.151
Whoa. This is heavy.

58:07.184 --> 58:09.153
There's that word again.
"Heavy."

58:09.186 --> 58:10.888
Why are things so heavy
in the future?

58:10.921 --> 58:12.590
Is there a problem
with the Earth's
gravitational pull?

58:12.823 --> 58:14.258
What?
The only way

58:14.291 --> 58:15.259
we're going to
get those two to
successfully mate

58:15.292 --> 58:17.094
is if they're
alone together,

58:17.127 --> 58:19.564
so you've got to
get your father and
mother to interact

58:19.597 --> 58:21.599
in some sort of social...

58:21.632 --> 58:23.267
(SIGHS)

58:23.300 --> 58:24.268
What? You mean
like a date?
Right!

58:24.301 --> 58:25.903
(BELL RINGING)

58:25.936 --> 58:27.037
What kind of date?
I don't know.

58:27.071 --> 58:28.906
What do kids do
in the '50s?

58:28.939 --> 58:31.576
They're your parents.
You must know them.

58:31.609 --> 58:32.877
What are their
common interests?

58:32.910 --> 58:34.178
What do they
like to do together?

58:35.345 --> 58:37.181
Nothing.

58:37.214 --> 58:40.184
Look! There's a rhythmic
ceremonial ritual coming up.

58:40.217 --> 58:42.219
Of course! The Enchantment
Under the Sea dance!

58:42.252 --> 58:43.854
They're supposed
to go to this.

58:43.888 --> 58:45.189
That's where they kiss
for the first time.

58:45.222 --> 58:46.991
All right, kid.

58:47.024 --> 58:48.893
You stick to
your father like glue

58:48.926 --> 58:49.827
and make sure
he takes her
to that dance.

58:50.628 --> 58:53.330
George, buddy.

58:53.363 --> 58:56.000
Remember that girl
I introduced you to,
Lorraine?

59:02.239 --> 59:03.974
What are you writing?

59:04.008 --> 59:05.843
Uh... Stories.

59:07.077 --> 59:11.248
Science fiction stories
about visitors

59:11.281 --> 59:13.951
coming down to Earth
from other planets.

59:16.887 --> 59:19.590
Get out of town!
I didn't know you
did anything creative.

59:20.257 --> 59:21.358
Let me read some.

59:21.391 --> 59:23.260
Oh. No, no, no, no.

59:23.293 --> 59:25.863
I never let anybody
read my stories.

59:26.897 --> 59:28.633
Why not?

59:28.866 --> 59:30.901
Well, what if they
didn't like them?

59:30.935 --> 59:32.603
What if they told me
I was no good?

59:35.940 --> 59:37.574
I guess that would be
pretty hard for somebody
to understand.

59:39.209 --> 59:41.578
No. No, not hard at all.

59:43.247 --> 59:45.215
So, anyway, George.
About Lorraine.

59:46.884 --> 59:48.218
She really likes you.

59:50.087 --> 59:52.957
She told me to tell you
that she wants you
to ask her

59:52.990 --> 59:54.358
to the Enchantment
Under the Sea dance.

59:54.391 --> 59:56.126
Really?
Oh, yeah.

59:56.160 --> 59:58.362
All you got to do
is go over there
and ask her.

01:00:00.164 --> 01:00:02.032
What?
Right here, right now,
in the cafeteria?

01:00:02.066 --> 01:00:03.968
What if she said no?

01:00:04.001 --> 01:00:06.203
I don't know if
I could take that
kind of a rejection.

01:00:07.738 --> 01:00:11.041
Besides,
I think she'd rather go
with somebody else.

01:00:12.409 --> 01:00:13.343
Who?

01:00:15.312 --> 01:00:16.313
Biff.

01:00:18.348 --> 01:00:19.316
Don't kid around.
Come on.

01:00:19.349 --> 01:00:21.151
I'm gonna leave.

01:00:21.185 --> 01:00:23.153
BIFF: You want it.
You know you want it.

01:00:23.187 --> 01:00:25.355
You know you want me
to give it to you.

01:00:25.389 --> 01:00:27.357
Shut your filthy mouth.
I'm not that kind of girl.

01:00:27.391 --> 01:00:29.159
(EXCLAIMS)

01:00:29.193 --> 01:00:32.029
Maybe you are
and you just
don't know it yet.

01:00:32.062 --> 01:00:33.430
Get your meat hooks
off of me.

01:00:33.463 --> 01:00:35.099
MARTY: You heard her.

01:00:35.132 --> 01:00:37.935
She said,
get your meat hooks off.

01:00:39.303 --> 01:00:40.337
Please.

01:00:41.772 --> 01:00:43.307
So what's it to you,
butthead?

01:00:45.075 --> 01:00:47.144
You know, you been
looking for a fight.

01:00:47.177 --> 01:00:48.078
(STUDENTS EXCLAIMING)

01:00:57.387 --> 01:01:00.691
Since you're new here,
I'm going to cut you
a break, today.

01:01:03.227 --> 01:01:06.230
So, why don't you
make like a tree
and get out of here.

01:01:15.105 --> 01:01:16.206
(BOY LAUGHING)

01:01:19.209 --> 01:01:20.044
George!

01:01:22.279 --> 01:01:24.348
Why do you keep
following me around?

01:01:24.381 --> 01:01:27.484
Look, George...
I'm telling you, George,

01:01:27.517 --> 01:01:29.286
if you do not
ask Lorraine
to that dance,

01:01:29.319 --> 01:01:30.454
I'm gonna regret it
for the rest of my life.

01:01:30.487 --> 01:01:32.489
But I can't go
to the dance.

01:01:32.522 --> 01:01:35.492
I'll miss my favorite
television program,
Science Fiction Theatre.

01:01:35.525 --> 01:01:38.495
Yeah, but, George,
Lorraine wants to
go with you.

01:01:38.528 --> 01:01:40.397
Give her a break.

01:01:40.430 --> 01:01:43.734
Look, I'm just not
ready to ask Lorraine
out to the dance,

01:01:45.235 --> 01:01:48.238
and not you or
anybody else
on this planet

01:01:48.272 --> 01:01:50.340
is going to make me
change my mind.

01:01:57.848 --> 01:01:59.249
MARTY:
Science Fiction Theatre.

01:02:12.162 --> 01:02:13.463
(MUFFLED BREATHING)

01:02:23.073 --> 01:02:24.441
(LOUD ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

01:02:28.112 --> 01:02:29.046
(MUSIC STOPS)

01:02:31.081 --> 01:02:32.216
Who are you?

01:02:32.249 --> 01:02:33.350
(MUSIC PLAYING)

01:02:36.420 --> 01:02:37.788
(MUSIC STOPS)

01:02:37.822 --> 01:02:39.389
MARTY: Silence, Earthling.

01:02:41.325 --> 01:02:43.360
My name is Darth Vader.

01:02:49.199 --> 01:02:51.869
I am an extraterrestrial
from the planet Vulcan.

01:02:54.204 --> 01:02:55.372
Marty!

01:02:55.405 --> 01:02:56.406
(HORN HONKING)

01:02:58.475 --> 01:02:59.576
Marty! Marty!

01:02:59.609 --> 01:03:01.411
Hey, George, buddy.

01:03:01.445 --> 01:03:03.447
You weren't at school.
What have you
been doing all day?

01:03:03.480 --> 01:03:06.516
I overslept.
Look, I need your help.

01:03:06.550 --> 01:03:08.285
I have to
ask Lorraine out,

01:03:08.318 --> 01:03:09.553
but I don't know
how to do it.

01:03:10.955 --> 01:03:11.889
All right. Okay, listen,
keep your pants on.
She's over in the cafe.

01:03:12.389 --> 01:03:13.824
God! How do you...

01:03:17.461 --> 01:03:19.229
What made you change
your mind, George?

01:03:19.263 --> 01:03:22.399
Last night,
Darth Vader came down
from Planet Vulcan

01:03:22.432 --> 01:03:26.470
and told me that if I
didn't take Lorraine out,
that he'd melt my brain.

01:03:26.503 --> 01:03:28.873
Let's just keep this
brain-melting stuff
to ourselves, okay?

01:03:28.906 --> 01:03:30.374
Oh, yeah. Yeah.

01:03:30.407 --> 01:03:32.609
All right, okay.
There she is, George.

01:03:32.642 --> 01:03:34.478
Now just go in there
and invite her.

01:03:34.511 --> 01:03:36.180
Okay. But I don't
know what to say.

01:03:36.213 --> 01:03:37.481
Just say anything,
George.

01:03:38.815 --> 01:03:40.885
Say whatever's natural,
the first thing that
comes into your mind.

01:03:42.119 --> 01:03:44.421
Nothing's coming
to my mind.

01:03:44.454 --> 01:03:45.489
Jesus, George,
it's a wonder
I was even born.

01:03:45.522 --> 01:03:46.857
What? What?

01:03:46.891 --> 01:03:49.159
Nothing.
Nothing. Nothing.

01:03:49.193 --> 01:03:53.230
Look, tell her destiny
brought you together.

01:03:53.263 --> 01:03:55.199
Tell her that she is
the most beautiful girl

01:03:55.232 --> 01:03:56.633
you have ever seen
in the world.

01:03:56.666 --> 01:03:59.269
Girls like that stuff.

01:03:59.303 --> 01:04:00.470
What are you doing,
George?

01:04:00.504 --> 01:04:02.239
I'm writing this down.
This is good stuff.

01:04:02.272 --> 01:04:04.174
Yeah. Okay, let's go.

01:04:04.208 --> 01:04:05.642
Can you
take care of that?
Right.

01:04:05.675 --> 01:04:07.912
(POP SONG PLAYING ON JUKEBOX)

01:04:10.280 --> 01:04:11.381
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

01:04:23.593 --> 01:04:26.330
Lou, give me a milk.

01:04:27.697 --> 01:04:29.166
Chocolate.

01:04:45.715 --> 01:04:50.387
Lorraine. My density
has popped me to you.

01:04:51.721 --> 01:04:53.290
What?

01:04:53.323 --> 01:04:54.258
Oh.

01:04:55.459 --> 01:04:58.595
What I meant
to say was...

01:04:58.628 --> 01:05:00.897
Wait a minute.
Don't I know you
from somewhere?

01:05:01.498 --> 01:05:03.300
GEORGE: Yes.

01:05:03.333 --> 01:05:06.536
Yes. I'm George.
George McFly.

01:05:07.504 --> 01:05:08.939
I'm your density.

01:05:10.274 --> 01:05:11.275
I mean,

01:05:12.742 --> 01:05:14.011
your destiny.

01:05:15.445 --> 01:05:16.346
Oh.

01:05:17.381 --> 01:05:18.949
Hey, McFly.

01:05:18.983 --> 01:05:19.950
(MUSIC STOPS)

01:05:20.484 --> 01:05:21.551
(EXCLAIMS)

01:05:23.487 --> 01:05:25.655
I thought I told you
never to come in here.

01:05:28.758 --> 01:05:31.328
Well, it's going
to cost you.

01:05:31.361 --> 01:05:33.697
How much money
you got on you?

01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:36.600
How much do
you want, Biff?

01:05:36.633 --> 01:05:37.634
(GRUNTS)
(ALL GASPING)

01:05:44.274 --> 01:05:45.609
All right, punk.

01:05:45.642 --> 01:05:47.011
Now I'm going to...

01:05:47.244 --> 01:05:48.312
Whoa, whoa, Biff.
What's that?

01:05:49.379 --> 01:05:50.414
(GRUNTS)

01:05:55.552 --> 01:05:58.455
That's Calvin Klein.
Oh, my God, he's a dream.

01:05:58.488 --> 01:05:59.556
Whoa, whoa.

01:05:59.589 --> 01:06:01.358
Kid! Kid, stop! Stop!

01:06:01.391 --> 01:06:02.392
Hey!

01:06:05.029 --> 01:06:05.529
MARTY: I'll get it
back to you, all right?

01:06:06.796 --> 01:06:08.398
BOY: You broke it!

01:06:08.798 --> 01:06:10.034
Come back here!

01:06:10.267 --> 01:06:11.001
(HORN HONKING)

01:06:12.436 --> 01:06:13.670
Wow. Look at him go!

01:06:15.672 --> 01:06:16.706
Get him!

01:06:30.520 --> 01:06:32.422
To the car!
Go! Go!

01:06:39.429 --> 01:06:40.397
GIRL: What's that
thing he's on?

01:06:40.430 --> 01:06:41.731
BOY: It's a board
with wheels.

01:06:41.765 --> 01:06:43.533
He's an absolute dream.

01:06:43.567 --> 01:06:44.734
THUG 1: Come on, come on!

01:06:44.768 --> 01:06:46.036
THUG 2: Look out for the car!

01:06:48.472 --> 01:06:49.673
(SHOUTING)

01:06:52.509 --> 01:06:53.777
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:06:59.783 --> 01:07:01.017
(SCREAMING)

01:07:01.851 --> 01:07:03.053
Whoa!

01:07:04.854 --> 01:07:06.123
(WOMAN GRUNTS)

01:07:08.692 --> 01:07:10.327
(TIRES SQUEALING)

01:07:18.335 --> 01:07:19.669
(LAUGHING)

01:07:19.703 --> 01:07:21.338
BIFF: I'm going
to ram him.

01:07:28.745 --> 01:07:29.679
ALL: Shit!

01:07:32.882 --> 01:07:33.817
(EXCLAIMS IN DISGUST)

01:07:41.491 --> 01:07:42.492
Ooh!

01:07:45.462 --> 01:07:46.696
(CROWD MURMURING)

01:07:55.205 --> 01:07:56.640
Thanks a lot, kid.

01:07:58.475 --> 01:08:00.677
I'm going to get
that son of a bitch.

01:08:00.710 --> 01:08:01.711
Where does
he come from?

01:08:01.745 --> 01:08:03.413
Yeah,
where does he live?

01:08:04.648 --> 01:08:07.617
I don't know,
but I'm going to find out.

01:08:10.187 --> 01:08:11.521
(VIDEO REWINDING)

01:08:13.790 --> 01:08:15.825
DOC ON TV: Oh, my God.

01:08:15.859 --> 01:08:18.728
They found me.
I don't know how,
but they found me.

01:08:18.762 --> 01:08:20.564
Run for it, Marty!

01:08:20.597 --> 01:08:21.631
(VIDEO REWINDING)

01:08:24.934 --> 01:08:27.704
Oh, my God.

01:08:27.737 --> 01:08:30.207
They found me.
I don't know how,
but they found me.

01:08:30.440 --> 01:08:31.408
Run for it, Marty!

01:08:32.709 --> 01:08:33.477
Doc?

01:08:34.811 --> 01:08:37.481
Hi, Marty. I didn't
hear you come in.

01:08:38.948 --> 01:08:40.817
Fascinating device,
this video unit.

01:08:42.219 --> 01:08:44.188
Listen, Doc.

01:08:44.221 --> 01:08:44.954
You know,
there's something

01:08:45.755 --> 01:08:46.623
I haven't told you
about the night

01:08:47.724 --> 01:08:48.425
we made that tape.
Please, Marty,
don't tell me.

01:08:49.659 --> 01:08:49.693
No man should know
too much about
his own destiny.

01:08:50.594 --> 01:08:50.627
You don't understand.
I do understand.

01:08:51.595 --> 01:08:51.628
If I know too much
about my own future,

01:08:52.429 --> 01:08:53.563
I can endanger
my own existence.

01:08:54.364 --> 01:08:55.432
Just as you've
endangered yours.

01:08:57.701 --> 01:08:59.936
You're right.
Now...

01:08:59.969 --> 01:09:02.772
Let me show you my plan
for sending you home.

01:09:02.806 --> 01:09:04.774
Please excuse the crudity
of this model.

01:09:04.808 --> 01:09:06.876
I didn't have time
to build it to scale
or paint it.

01:09:06.910 --> 01:09:08.512
It's good.
Thank you. Thank you.

01:09:09.813 --> 01:09:11.648
Okay, now.

01:09:11.681 --> 01:09:13.850
We run some
industrial-strength
electrical cable

01:09:13.883 --> 01:09:15.685
from the top of
the clock tower

01:09:15.719 --> 01:09:17.221
down, suspending it
over the street

01:09:17.454 --> 01:09:19.923
between these
two lamp posts.

01:09:19.956 --> 01:09:21.958
Meanwhile,
we've outfitted
the time vehicle

01:09:21.991 --> 01:09:23.893
with this big pole
and hook,

01:09:23.927 --> 01:09:27.964
which runs directly
into the flux capacitor.

01:09:27.997 --> 01:09:32.536
At the calculated moment,
you start off
from down the street,

01:09:32.569 --> 01:09:33.703
driving directly
toward the cable,

01:09:33.737 --> 01:09:37.541
accelerating to
88 miles per hour.

01:09:37.574 --> 01:09:40.777
According to the flyer,
at precisely 10:04 p.m.
this Saturday night,

01:09:40.810 --> 01:09:44.214
lightning will
strike the clock tower,
electrifying the cable

01:09:44.248 --> 01:09:46.716
just as the connecting
hook makes contact

01:09:46.750 --> 01:09:50.520
thereby sending
1.21 gigawatts
into the flux capacitor

01:09:50.554 --> 01:09:52.789
and sending you
back to 1985.

01:09:52.822 --> 01:09:54.758
All right, now.
Watch this.

01:09:54.791 --> 01:09:56.260
You wind up the car
and release it.

01:09:58.628 --> 01:10:00.730
I'll simulate
the lightning.

01:10:00.764 --> 01:10:02.232
(WIND-UP MECHANISM TWISTING)

01:10:02.266 --> 01:10:03.633
(ELECTRICAL HUMMING)

01:10:08.738 --> 01:10:09.739
Ready.

01:10:19.749 --> 01:10:20.684
Set.

01:10:25.889 --> 01:10:27.023
Release.

01:10:27.056 --> 01:10:28.525
(CAR WHIRRING)

01:10:30.994 --> 01:10:31.961
(EXCLAIMS)

01:10:39.303 --> 01:10:40.537
(GASPS)

01:10:45.975 --> 01:10:48.312
You're instilling me
with a lot of confidence,
Doc.

01:10:48.545 --> 01:10:49.613
Don't worry.
I'll take care
of the lightning.

01:10:49.646 --> 01:10:51.681
You take care
of your pop.

01:10:53.817 --> 01:10:55.952
By the way,
what happened today?
Did he ask her out?

01:10:55.985 --> 01:10:57.354
I think so.

01:10:57.387 --> 01:10:58.788
What did she say?

01:10:58.822 --> 01:10:59.789
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

01:11:07.364 --> 01:11:09.032
It's your mom!
She's tracked you down!

01:11:09.065 --> 01:11:10.834
Quick! Let's cover
the time machine.

01:11:24.681 --> 01:11:26.716
Hi, Cal... Marty.

01:11:27.417 --> 01:11:28.685
Mom. Lorraine.

01:11:30.820 --> 01:11:32.356
How did you know
I was here?

01:11:33.623 --> 01:11:34.824
I followed you.

01:11:35.959 --> 01:11:38.362
Oh. This is my doc...

01:11:38.395 --> 01:11:40.830
(STUTTERS) My uncle,
Doc Brown.

01:11:42.599 --> 01:11:43.400
Hi.
Hi.

01:11:47.003 --> 01:11:50.774
Marty, this may
seem a little forward,

01:11:50.807 --> 01:11:54.978
but I was
kind of wondering
if you'd ask me

01:11:55.011 --> 01:11:58.047
to the Enchantment
Under the Sea dance
on Saturday.

01:12:01.751 --> 01:12:03.987
Wow, you mean...
You mean nobody's
asked you?

01:12:04.988 --> 01:12:07.824
No. Not yet.

01:12:09.826 --> 01:12:11.361
What about George?

01:12:11.395 --> 01:12:12.896
George McFly?

01:12:15.932 --> 01:12:19.636
He's kind of cute
and all, but not...

01:12:20.870 --> 01:12:24.641
Well, I think
a man should be strong,

01:12:26.910 --> 01:12:28.778
so he can stand up
for himself

01:12:30.414 --> 01:12:31.915
and protect
the woman he loves.

01:12:36.920 --> 01:12:37.987
Don't you?

01:12:39.823 --> 01:12:41.758
Yeah.

01:12:41.791 --> 01:12:44.060
I still
don't understand.

01:12:44.093 --> 01:12:46.930
How am I supposed to
go to the dance with her

01:12:46.963 --> 01:12:49.899
if she's already going
to the dance with you?

01:12:49.933 --> 01:12:52.469
Well, because, George,
she wants to go with you.

01:12:52.702 --> 01:12:54.404
She just doesn't
know it yet.

01:12:54.438 --> 01:12:55.204
That's why
we got to show her

01:12:56.072 --> 01:12:58.007
that you, George McFly,
are a fighter.

01:12:58.041 --> 01:12:59.476
You're somebody
who's gonna stand up
for yourself,

01:12:59.709 --> 01:13:01.745
somebody who's
gonna protect her.

01:13:01.778 --> 01:13:04.748
Yeah, but I've never
picked a fight
in my entire life.

01:13:04.781 --> 01:13:07.016
Look, you're not going
to be picking a fight,
Dad.

01:13:07.050 --> 01:13:09.786
(STUTTERS) Daddy-o.

01:13:09.819 --> 01:13:11.888
You're coming to
her rescue, right?

01:13:11.921 --> 01:13:13.122
Okay, let's go over
the plan again.

01:13:13.156 --> 01:13:14.924
8:55, where are
you going to be?

01:13:14.958 --> 01:13:16.793
I'm going to be
at the dance.

01:13:16.826 --> 01:13:17.827
Right. And where
am I going to be?

01:13:18.662 --> 01:13:19.896
You're gonna be
in the car with her.

01:13:19.929 --> 01:13:21.197
Right, okay.
So, right around 9:00,

01:13:21.230 --> 01:13:23.032
she's going to get
very angry with me.

01:13:23.066 --> 01:13:25.502
Why is she going to
get angry with you?

01:13:25.535 --> 01:13:27.871
Well, because, George,
nice girls get angry

01:13:27.904 --> 01:13:29.706
when guys take
advantage of them.

01:13:30.840 --> 01:13:32.476
(EXCLAIMS)

01:13:32.709 --> 01:13:34.143
You mean
you're going to go
touch her on her...

01:13:34.177 --> 01:13:36.446
No. No, George, look.

01:13:37.781 --> 01:13:40.484
It's just an act, right?

01:13:40.717 --> 01:13:43.953
Okay. So, 9:00,
you're strolling through
the parking lot.

01:13:43.987 --> 01:13:47.824
You see us struggling
in the car.

01:13:47.857 --> 01:13:50.126
You walk up,
you open the door,
and you say...

01:13:52.095 --> 01:13:53.730
Your line, George.

01:13:55.031 --> 01:13:57.133
Oh!

01:13:57.166 --> 01:13:59.536
Hey, you, get your
damn hands off her!

01:14:02.271 --> 01:14:03.540
You really think
I ought to swear?

01:14:03.773 --> 01:14:04.841
Yes, definitely.

01:14:04.874 --> 01:14:06.776
God damn it,
George, swear.

01:14:06.810 --> 01:14:08.545
Okay.
So, now you come up.

01:14:08.578 --> 01:14:09.946
You punch me
in the stomach.

01:14:09.979 --> 01:14:12.015
I'm out for
the count, right?

01:14:12.048 --> 01:14:14.984
And you and Lorraine
live happily ever after.

01:14:15.018 --> 01:14:17.253
You make it
sound so easy.

01:14:17.286 --> 01:14:19.923
I just... I wish
I wasn't so scared.

01:14:19.956 --> 01:14:21.257
George, there's nothing
to be scared of.

01:14:21.290 --> 01:14:24.027
All it takes is
a little self-confidence.

01:14:24.060 --> 01:14:26.863
You know, if you
put your mind to it,

01:14:26.896 --> 01:14:27.764
you can
accomplish anything.

01:14:31.200 --> 01:14:33.236
ANNOUNCER:
...Hill Valley area weather
this Saturday night.

01:14:33.269 --> 01:14:36.005
Mostly clear,
with some scattered clouds.

01:14:36.039 --> 01:14:37.974
Lows tonight in
the upper 40s.

01:14:38.007 --> 01:14:41.077
Are you sure
about this storm?

01:14:41.110 --> 01:14:45.915
Since when can weathermen
predict the weather,
let alone the future?

01:14:45.949 --> 01:14:48.217
You know, Marty,
I'm going to be very sad
to see you go.

01:14:48.251 --> 01:14:49.185
You've really made
a difference in my life.

01:14:50.053 --> 01:14:51.120
You've given me
something to shoot for.

01:14:52.221 --> 01:14:55.959
Just knowing that
I'm going to be around
to see 1985.

01:14:55.992 --> 01:14:58.027
That I'm going to
succeed in this!

01:14:58.061 --> 01:15:00.930
That I'm going
to have a chance
to travel through time!

01:15:07.604 --> 01:15:10.039
It's going to be
really hard waiting 30 years
before I can talk to you

01:15:10.073 --> 01:15:12.576
about everything
that's happened
in the past few days.

01:15:12.809 --> 01:15:14.878
I'm really going
to miss you, Marty.

01:15:16.580 --> 01:15:17.947
I'm really going
to miss you.

01:15:22.619 --> 01:15:23.620
Doc, about the future...

01:15:23.653 --> 01:15:25.922
No!

01:15:25.955 --> 01:15:28.157
Marty!
We've already agreed

01:15:28.191 --> 01:15:29.593
that having information
about the future

01:15:29.826 --> 01:15:31.094
can be
extremely dangerous.

01:15:31.127 --> 01:15:32.596
Even if your
intentions are good,

01:15:32.829 --> 01:15:34.130
it can backfire
drastically.

01:15:36.065 --> 01:15:37.166
Whatever you've
got to tell me,

01:15:38.201 --> 01:15:39.903
I'll find out through
the natural course of time.

01:15:41.104 --> 01:15:42.906
"Dear Dr. Brown.

01:15:44.173 --> 01:15:46.042
"On the night that
I go back in time,

01:15:46.843 --> 01:15:48.177
"you will be

01:15:49.178 --> 01:15:51.114
"shot by terrorists.

01:15:53.216 --> 01:15:55.318
"Please take
whatever precautions
are necessary

01:15:55.351 --> 01:15:57.220
"to prevent
this terrible disaster.

01:15:59.022 --> 01:16:00.256
"Your friend,

01:16:01.390 --> 01:16:02.659
"Marty."

01:16:12.702 --> 01:16:15.605
'Evening, Dr. Brown.
What's with the wire?

01:16:15.639 --> 01:16:18.074
Oh, just a little
weather experiment.

01:16:20.276 --> 01:16:21.244
What you got
under here?

01:16:21.277 --> 01:16:22.245
No! Don't touch that!

01:16:22.879 --> 01:16:25.248
Some new, specialized
weather-sensing equipment.

01:16:25.281 --> 01:16:27.383
You got a permit
for that?

01:16:27.416 --> 01:16:28.584
Of course I do.

01:16:36.926 --> 01:16:39.162
Just a second.
Let me see if
I can find it here.

01:16:40.429 --> 01:16:42.331
(ROCK 'N' ROLL MUSIC PLAYING)

01:17:28.311 --> 01:17:29.378
(SIGHS)

01:17:32.015 --> 01:17:35.952
Do you mind if we
park for a while?

01:17:37.486 --> 01:17:39.222
That's a great idea.
I'd love to park.

01:17:39.255 --> 01:17:40.724
Huh?

01:17:40.757 --> 01:17:43.459
Marty, I'm almost
18 years old.

01:17:43.492 --> 01:17:45.028
It's not like I've
never parked before.

01:17:45.995 --> 01:17:48.197
What?

01:17:48.231 --> 01:17:50.734
Marty, you seem so nervous.
Is something wrong?

01:17:50.967 --> 01:17:51.768
No.

01:17:53.069 --> 01:17:54.037
No.

01:17:59.242 --> 01:18:02.278
Lorraine! Lorraine,
what are you doing?

01:18:02.311 --> 01:18:04.480
I swiped it from
the old lady's
liquor cabinet.

01:18:04.513 --> 01:18:07.183
Yeah, well,
you shouldn't drink.

01:18:07.216 --> 01:18:08.251
Why not?

01:18:08.284 --> 01:18:09.118
Because you...

01:18:10.253 --> 01:18:12.455
You might regret it
later in life.

01:18:14.257 --> 01:18:16.092
Marty, don't be
such a square.

01:18:16.125 --> 01:18:17.426
Everybody who's
anybody drinks.

01:18:23.132 --> 01:18:24.233
Jeez, you smoke, too?

01:18:26.770 --> 01:18:29.038
Marty, you're
beginning to sound
just like my mother.

01:18:34.277 --> 01:18:35.511
(JAZZ MUSIC ENDING)

01:18:35.544 --> 01:18:37.213
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

01:18:41.050 --> 01:18:42.051
We're going to
take a little break,

01:18:42.952 --> 01:18:43.753
but we'll be back
in a while,

01:18:44.687 --> 01:18:45.789
so don't nobody
go nowhere.

01:19:02.505 --> 01:19:05.374
Marty?
Why are you so nervous?

01:19:07.043 --> 01:19:08.144
Lorraine.

01:19:09.378 --> 01:19:14.183
Have you ever
been in a situation

01:19:14.217 --> 01:19:15.484
where you knew
you had to act
a certain way,

01:19:15.518 --> 01:19:18.121
but when you got there,
you didn't know

01:19:18.154 --> 01:19:20.123
if you could go
through with it?

01:19:20.156 --> 01:19:23.092
You mean like
how you're supposed
to act on a first date?

01:19:23.126 --> 01:19:23.927
Sort of.

01:19:25.361 --> 01:19:27.430
I think I know
exactly what you mean.

01:19:28.464 --> 01:19:30.499
You do?

01:19:30.533 --> 01:19:32.869
You know what I do
in those situations?

01:19:32.902 --> 01:19:34.270
What?

01:19:34.303 --> 01:19:35.338
I don't worry.

01:19:35.371 --> 01:19:36.806
(MUFFLED SHOUTING)

01:19:53.556 --> 01:19:56.559
This is all wrong.
I don't know what it is.

01:19:59.095 --> 01:20:01.831
But when I kiss you,
it's like I'm kissing

01:20:03.933 --> 01:20:05.869
my brother.

01:20:06.102 --> 01:20:08.471
I guess that doesn't
make any sense, does it?

01:20:08.504 --> 01:20:12.441
Believe me,
it makes perfect sense.

01:20:12.475 --> 01:20:14.210
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

01:20:14.243 --> 01:20:15.511
Somebody's coming.

01:20:20.549 --> 01:20:24.854
You caused 300 bucks
damage to my car,
you son of a bitch.

01:20:24.888 --> 01:20:27.223
And I'm going to
take it out of your ass.
Hold him.

01:20:28.457 --> 01:20:30.426
Let him go, Biff.
You're drunk.

01:20:32.128 --> 01:20:33.829
Well, look-ey
what we have here.

01:20:37.366 --> 01:20:40.503
No, no! You're staying
right here with me.
Come on, Lorraine.

01:20:40.536 --> 01:20:41.938
LORRAINE: Let me go!

01:20:41.971 --> 01:20:43.606
Leave her alone,
you bastard!

01:20:43.639 --> 01:20:45.508
Take him in back,
all right?
I'll be right there.

01:20:45.541 --> 01:20:48.511
BIFF: Just admit
that you want it.
Come on.

01:20:48.544 --> 01:20:50.246
Well, go on.
This ain't no peep show.

01:20:50.679 --> 01:20:51.847
(GRUNTS)

01:20:53.349 --> 01:20:54.617
(LORRAINE SHOUTING)

01:20:57.386 --> 01:20:58.321
Hey, let's put him
in there.

01:20:58.354 --> 01:20:59.422
Yeah! (LAUGHS)

01:21:01.490 --> 01:21:03.626
That's for
messing up my hair.

01:21:03.659 --> 01:21:05.929
What the hell are
you doing to my car?

01:21:06.162 --> 01:21:07.931
Hey, beat it, spook.
This don't concern you.

01:21:11.200 --> 01:21:13.202
Who you calling "spook,"
peckerwood?

01:21:15.004 --> 01:21:16.940
Hey, hey,
listen, guys...

01:21:17.173 --> 01:21:19.375
Look, I don't want
to mess with no
reefer addicts, okay?

01:21:19.408 --> 01:21:21.244
Get home to
your mama, boy.

01:21:21.277 --> 01:21:22.411
THUG 1: Biff!

01:21:22.445 --> 01:21:24.247
THUG 2: Hurry, Biff!

01:21:24.280 --> 01:21:25.481
MARTY: (MUFFLED)
Let me out of here!

01:21:28.017 --> 01:21:29.485
Reginald,
where are your keys?

01:21:29.518 --> 01:21:31.220
MARTY: The keys
are in the trunk.

01:21:31.654 --> 01:21:33.389
Say that again?

01:21:33.422 --> 01:21:34.523
MARTY: I said,
the keys are in here.

01:21:40.363 --> 01:21:41.464
(LORRAINE SHOUTING)

01:21:48.471 --> 01:21:49.372
BIFF: Come on!

01:21:52.441 --> 01:21:54.443
Hey, you,
get your damn hands off...

01:21:56.412 --> 01:21:58.314
Oh.

01:21:58.347 --> 01:22:00.349
I think you got
the wrong car, McFly.

01:22:02.018 --> 01:22:04.420
George, help me!
Please!

01:22:04.453 --> 01:22:06.522
Just turn around, McFly,
and walk away.

01:22:08.024 --> 01:22:08.992
LORRAINE: Please, George.

01:22:09.225 --> 01:22:10.359
Are you deaf, McFly?

01:22:10.393 --> 01:22:12.328
Close the door
and beat it.

01:22:12.361 --> 01:22:13.429
(WHIMPERING)

01:22:15.298 --> 01:22:18.234
No, Biff.
You leave her alone.

01:22:19.302 --> 01:22:20.603
All right, McFly.

01:22:24.740 --> 01:22:27.510
You're asking for it,
and now you're
going to get it.

01:22:29.512 --> 01:22:30.446
(GROANING)
Biff, stop it!

01:22:32.015 --> 01:22:33.649
Biff, you'll
break his arm!

01:22:34.383 --> 01:22:35.418
(GASPING)

01:22:35.451 --> 01:22:36.319
Biff, no!

01:22:37.753 --> 01:22:40.056
MARVIN: Give me
a hand here, Reginald.

01:22:40.089 --> 01:22:41.457
(GROANING)

01:22:41.490 --> 01:22:43.692
Damn it, man!
I sliced my hand!

01:22:43.726 --> 01:22:45.061
Whose are these?
Mine.

01:22:45.294 --> 01:22:46.662
Thanks. Thanks a lot.

01:22:48.564 --> 01:22:49.999
You're going to
break his arm!

01:22:51.300 --> 01:22:54.370
Biff! Biff,
leave him alone!

01:22:54.403 --> 01:22:56.405
Let him go!
Let him go!

01:22:59.808 --> 01:23:01.277
(LAUGHING)

01:23:10.753 --> 01:23:12.021
(GRUNTS)

01:23:18.427 --> 01:23:19.695
(GEORGE PANTING)

01:23:26.302 --> 01:23:27.403
(LAUGHS)

01:23:29.638 --> 01:23:31.074
Are you okay?

01:23:51.527 --> 01:23:53.696
Who is that guy?

01:23:53.729 --> 01:23:54.697
That's George McFly.

01:23:58.867 --> 01:24:00.836
That's George McFly?

01:24:00.869 --> 01:24:02.071
Excuse me.

01:24:04.673 --> 01:24:06.142
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

01:24:09.678 --> 01:24:11.080
(WIND BLOWING)

01:24:13.516 --> 01:24:14.750
The storm.

01:24:17.620 --> 01:24:19.855
Hey, guys, you gotta
get back in there
and finish the dance.

01:24:19.888 --> 01:24:21.624
Hey, man.
Look at Marvin's hand.

01:24:21.657 --> 01:24:22.758
He can't play with
his hand like that,

01:24:22.791 --> 01:24:23.792
and we can't
play without him.

01:24:24.727 --> 01:24:26.795
Yeah, well.
Look, Marvin,
you got to play.

01:24:26.829 --> 01:24:28.697
See, that's where they
kiss for the first time
on the dance floor.

01:24:28.731 --> 01:24:30.699
And if there's no music,
they can't dance.

01:24:30.733 --> 01:24:32.201
If they can't dance,
they can't kiss.

01:24:33.569 --> 01:24:34.270
If they can't kiss,
they can't fall in love
and I'm history.

01:24:34.303 --> 01:24:35.771
Hey, man,
the dance is over

01:24:36.972 --> 01:24:37.640
unless you know
somebody else that
can play the guitar.

01:24:45.714 --> 01:24:47.516
This is for all
you lovers out there.

01:24:50.653 --> 01:24:54.123
MARVIN: (SINGING)
Earth angel, Earth angel

01:24:55.424 --> 01:24:57.560
Will you be mine?

01:24:58.494 --> 01:25:00.729
My darling dear

01:25:01.897 --> 01:25:03.666
George, aren't you
going to kiss me?

01:25:03.699 --> 01:25:04.833
I don't know.

01:25:07.236 --> 01:25:09.438
Scram, McFly.
I'm cutting in.

01:25:09.472 --> 01:25:10.206
(LORRAINE GRUNTING)

01:25:13.942 --> 01:25:16.179
(DISSONANT NOTES PLAYING)

01:25:16.412 --> 01:25:19.782
Earth angel, Earth angel

01:25:20.816 --> 01:25:22.785
The one I adore

01:25:22.818 --> 01:25:24.520
Hey, boy,
you all right?

01:25:25.821 --> 01:25:27.223
I can't play.

01:25:27.256 --> 01:25:28.191
George!

01:25:29.592 --> 01:25:30.693
(LAUGHING)

01:25:45.841 --> 01:25:46.842
George!

01:25:48.611 --> 01:25:49.578
George.

01:25:52.715 --> 01:25:53.849
Excuse me.

01:25:54.717 --> 01:25:55.718
(GRUNTS)

01:26:03.792 --> 01:26:05.894
The vision of your happiness

01:26:08.597 --> 01:26:11.500
Earth angel, Earth angel

01:26:12.301 --> 01:26:15.271
Please be mine

01:26:16.004 --> 01:26:18.707
My darling dear

01:26:18.741 --> 01:26:21.510
Love you for all time

01:26:22.545 --> 01:26:25.514
I'm just a fool

01:26:26.749 --> 01:26:29.618
A fool in love

01:26:30.886 --> 01:26:34.223
with you

01:26:39.862 --> 01:26:41.730
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

01:26:41.764 --> 01:26:45.268
Yeah, man, that was good.
Let's do another one.

01:26:45.501 --> 01:26:47.770
No. I got to go.

01:26:47.803 --> 01:26:50.873
Come on, man.
Let's do something
that really cooks.

01:26:50.906 --> 01:26:53.542
Something that cooks.

01:26:54.310 --> 01:26:55.578
(ALL CHEERING)

01:26:58.981 --> 01:27:00.316
All right.

01:27:00.349 --> 01:27:00.916
MARVIN: All right!

01:27:05.288 --> 01:27:06.322
All right.

01:27:07.856 --> 01:27:10.693
All right,
this is an oldie, but...

01:27:13.562 --> 01:27:15.931
Well, it's an oldie
where I come from.

01:27:18.801 --> 01:27:21.003
All right, guys, listen,
this is a blues riff in B.

01:27:21.036 --> 01:27:23.872
Watch me for the changes,
and try and keep up, okay?

01:27:23.906 --> 01:27:25.774
(ROCK 'N' ROLL MUSIC PLAYING)

01:27:41.089 --> 01:27:43.892
(SINGING)
Way down in Louisiana
Down in New Orleans

01:27:43.926 --> 01:27:46.829
Way back up in the woods
among the evergreens

01:27:46.862 --> 01:27:49.932
There stood a log cabin
made of earth and wood

01:27:49.965 --> 01:27:52.668
Where lived a country boy
name of Johnny B. Goode

01:27:52.701 --> 01:27:55.371
He never ever learned
to read or write so well

01:27:55.604 --> 01:27:57.840
He could play the guitar
just like he's ringing a bell

01:27:57.873 --> 01:28:01.276
Go, go
Go, Johnny, go, go

01:28:02.044 --> 01:28:03.812
Go, Johnny, go, go, go

01:28:04.980 --> 01:28:06.949
Go, Johnny, go, go

01:28:06.982 --> 01:28:09.718
Hey, George, I heard
you laid out Biff.
Nice going.

01:28:09.752 --> 01:28:11.687
George, you ever
think of running
for class president?

01:28:11.720 --> 01:28:13.822
Johnny B. Goode

01:28:16.659 --> 01:28:19.094
Go, Johnny, go, go

01:28:19.127 --> 01:28:21.964
Go, Johnny, go, go, go

01:28:21.997 --> 01:28:24.833
Go, Johnny, go, go

01:28:24.867 --> 01:28:26.769
Go, Johnny, go, go, go

01:28:28.704 --> 01:28:30.038
Johnny B. Goode

01:28:32.908 --> 01:28:35.844
Chuck!
Chuck, it's Marvin.

01:28:35.878 --> 01:28:38.647
Your cousin,
Marvin Berry.

01:28:38.681 --> 01:28:41.016
You know that new sound
you're looking for?

01:28:41.049 --> 01:28:42.751
Well, listen to this.

01:29:06.842 --> 01:29:08.811
(HEAVY METAL RIFFS PLAYING)

01:29:28.797 --> 01:29:29.898
(FEEDBACK)

01:29:33.201 --> 01:29:35.404
(HIGH-PITCH NOTE PLAYING)

01:29:38.841 --> 01:29:40.108
(AMPLIFIERS HUMMING)

01:29:53.088 --> 01:29:55.123
I guess you guys aren't
ready for that yet.

01:29:57.092 --> 01:29:58.093
But your kids are
going to love it.

01:29:59.061 --> 01:30:00.729
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

01:30:02.765 --> 01:30:04.433
Lorraine.

01:30:04.467 --> 01:30:06.802
Marty, that was
very interesting music.

01:30:06.835 --> 01:30:08.103
Yeah.

01:30:08.971 --> 01:30:10.806
I hope you don't mind,

01:30:10.839 --> 01:30:12.941
but George asked if
he could take me home.

01:30:12.975 --> 01:30:15.944
Great! Good.
Good, Lorraine.

01:30:15.978 --> 01:30:16.979
I had a feeling
about you two.

01:30:17.846 --> 01:30:20.048
I have a feeling, too.

01:30:20.082 --> 01:30:21.884
Listen, I got to go,

01:30:21.917 --> 01:30:25.954
but I wanted to tell you
that it's been educational.

01:30:27.523 --> 01:30:29.458
Marty, will we ever
see you again?

01:30:30.959 --> 01:30:32.828
I guarantee it.

01:30:32.861 --> 01:30:35.831
Well, Marty,
I want to thank you for
all your good advice.

01:30:35.864 --> 01:30:37.866
I'll never forget it.

01:30:38.867 --> 01:30:40.035
Right, George.

01:30:42.004 --> 01:30:44.973
Well, good luck,
you guys.

01:30:46.809 --> 01:30:47.743
Oh!

01:30:49.878 --> 01:30:53.549
One other thing.
If you guys
ever have kids,

01:30:53.582 --> 01:30:55.984
and one of them,
when he's eight years old,

01:30:56.018 --> 01:30:58.487
accidentally sets fire
to the living room rug,

01:31:00.022 --> 01:31:01.490
go easy on him.

01:31:02.758 --> 01:31:03.826
Okay.

01:31:09.097 --> 01:31:11.500
Marty.
Such a nice name.

01:31:16.304 --> 01:31:17.840
(WIND HOWLING)

01:31:17.873 --> 01:31:19.542
Damn!
Where is that kid?

01:31:22.978 --> 01:31:24.012
Damn!

01:31:26.882 --> 01:31:27.916
Damn! Damn!

01:31:31.019 --> 01:31:32.254
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:31:36.625 --> 01:31:39.127
You're late!
Do you have no
concept of time?

01:31:39.161 --> 01:31:41.597
Hey, come on.
I had to change.

01:31:41.830 --> 01:31:44.900
Do you think
I'm going back
in that zoot suit?

01:31:44.933 --> 01:31:47.302
The old man really
came through. It worked.

01:31:47.335 --> 01:31:49.605
He laid out Biff
in one punch.

01:31:49.638 --> 01:31:50.973
I didn't know
he had it in him.

01:31:51.006 --> 01:31:53.275
He's never stood up
to Biff in his life.

01:31:55.043 --> 01:31:56.311
Never?

01:31:56.344 --> 01:31:57.880
No. Why?
What's the matter?

01:31:59.347 --> 01:32:02.585
All right! Let's set
your destination time.

01:32:05.954 --> 01:32:07.923
(MACHINE BEEPING)

01:32:07.956 --> 01:32:10.593
This is the exact time
you left.

01:32:10.826 --> 01:32:13.562
Let's send you back at
exactly the same time.

01:32:16.965 --> 01:32:18.601
It'll be like
you never left.

01:32:21.169 --> 01:32:25.207
Now, I painted a white line
on the street way over there.

01:32:25.240 --> 01:32:27.309
That's where
you'll start from.

01:32:27.342 --> 01:32:29.912
I've calculated
the precise distance,

01:32:29.945 --> 01:32:32.280
taking into account
the acceleration speed

01:32:32.314 --> 01:32:34.282
and wind resistance
retroactive

01:32:34.316 --> 01:32:37.219
from the moment
the lightning strikes,

01:32:37.252 --> 01:32:42.090
which will be in exactly
7 minutes and 22 seconds.

01:32:42.124 --> 01:32:44.092
When this alarm goes off,
you hit the gas.

01:32:44.126 --> 01:32:44.993
Right.

01:32:52.334 --> 01:32:54.903
Well, I guess
that's everything.

01:32:59.241 --> 01:33:00.676
Thanks.

01:33:00.709 --> 01:33:01.877
Thank you.

01:33:07.182 --> 01:33:08.984
See you
in about 30 years.

01:33:10.886 --> 01:33:12.020
I hope so.

01:33:13.989 --> 01:33:15.157
Don't worry!

01:33:16.324 --> 01:33:18.226
As long as you
hit that wire

01:33:18.260 --> 01:33:21.363
with the connecting hook
at precisely 88 miles
an hour,

01:33:21.396 --> 01:33:23.899
the instant the lightning
strikes the tower

01:33:26.702 --> 01:33:27.670
everything will be fine.

01:33:27.703 --> 01:33:28.637
Right.

01:33:36.178 --> 01:33:38.013
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

01:33:38.046 --> 01:33:40.115
What's the meaning
of this?

01:33:40.148 --> 01:33:41.717
You'll find out
in 30 years.

01:33:41.950 --> 01:33:44.019
It's about the future,
isn't it?

01:33:44.052 --> 01:33:44.720
It's information
about the future.

01:33:44.953 --> 01:33:46.989
Wait a minute.

01:33:47.022 --> 01:33:49.024
I warned you
about this, kid.

01:33:49.057 --> 01:33:52.027
The consequences
could be disastrous!

01:33:52.060 --> 01:33:54.062
Doc, that's a risk
you're going to
have to take.

01:33:54.096 --> 01:33:55.330
Your life depends on it!

01:33:55.363 --> 01:33:57.365
No!

01:33:57.399 --> 01:34:01.336
I refuse to accept
the responsibility.

01:34:01.369 --> 01:34:03.071
In that case,
I'll tell you
straight out.

01:34:03.105 --> 01:34:04.106
(THUNDER CRASHING)

01:34:07.710 --> 01:34:08.944
Great Scott!

01:34:12.480 --> 01:34:13.381
(THUNDER CLAPPING)

01:34:17.319 --> 01:34:20.188
You get the cable,
I'll throw the rope
down to you.

01:34:20.222 --> 01:34:21.690
Right! I got it!

01:34:24.359 --> 01:34:25.427
(WIND HOWLING)

01:34:53.188 --> 01:34:54.289
(GASPING)

01:34:56.124 --> 01:34:57.125
Doc!

01:35:03.431 --> 01:35:05.133
(GRUNTING)

01:35:05.167 --> 01:35:07.035
Come on, come on.
Let's go!

01:35:07.069 --> 01:35:09.137
All right!
Take it up!

01:35:12.407 --> 01:35:13.341
Go!

01:35:20.548 --> 01:35:21.516
Doc!

01:35:21.549 --> 01:35:23.251
What?

01:35:23.285 --> 01:35:26.388
I have to tell you
about the future.

01:35:26.421 --> 01:35:28.056
What?

01:35:28.090 --> 01:35:30.826
I have to tell you
about the future!

01:35:31.059 --> 01:35:32.761
What?

01:35:32.795 --> 01:35:37.365
On the night I go
back in time, you get...

01:35:37.399 --> 01:35:38.333
(CLOCK BELL TOLLING)

01:35:40.568 --> 01:35:41.770
Doc!

01:35:47.810 --> 01:35:49.077
(SCREAMING)

01:35:51.179 --> 01:35:52.247
Go!

01:35:53.315 --> 01:35:54.482
No, Doc!

01:35:54.516 --> 01:35:56.484
Look at the time!

01:35:56.518 --> 01:35:59.487
You've got less
than four minutes.
Please, hurry!

01:36:11.333 --> 01:36:12.467
Yeah!

01:36:27.449 --> 01:36:28.450
(GRUNTS)

01:37:06.521 --> 01:37:09.424
Damn it, Doc!
Why did you have to
tear up that letter?

01:37:09.457 --> 01:37:11.193
If I only had more time.

01:37:14.596 --> 01:37:17.399
Wait a minute.
I got all the time I want.

01:37:17.432 --> 01:37:20.602
I got a time machine.
I can just go back early
and warn him.

01:37:20.635 --> 01:37:22.837
Okay. Ten minutes
ought to do it.

01:37:23.906 --> 01:37:25.640
(BEEPING)

01:37:25.673 --> 01:37:30.378
Okay. Time circuit's on.
Flux capacitor, fluxing.

01:37:30.412 --> 01:37:32.447
Engine running.
All right.

01:37:32.480 --> 01:37:33.481
(ENGINE STOPS)

01:37:35.283 --> 01:37:37.385
No. No, no.

01:37:37.419 --> 01:37:39.254
(ENGINE STALLING)

01:37:39.287 --> 01:37:40.855
Come on. Not this time.
Come on. Come on.

01:37:58.206 --> 01:37:59.307
(GRUNTING)

01:38:01.209 --> 01:38:02.277
(SCREAMING)

01:38:09.184 --> 01:38:10.418
(ENGINE CLICKING)

01:38:15.423 --> 01:38:16.424
(GRUNTS)

01:38:39.281 --> 01:38:40.315
(GASPS)

01:38:48.723 --> 01:38:50.025
(GRUNTS)

01:38:51.626 --> 01:38:52.494
MARTY: Come on.
(ALARM RINGS)

01:38:55.363 --> 01:38:57.632
Here we go. Here we go.
This time. Come on.

01:38:59.501 --> 01:39:01.970
Please. Please.
Come on!

01:39:02.537 --> 01:39:03.605
(SHOUTS)

01:39:03.638 --> 01:39:04.672
(ENGINE STARTING)

01:39:06.274 --> 01:39:07.475
(EXCLAIMS)

01:39:07.509 --> 01:39:08.977
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:39:43.545 --> 01:39:44.546
(GASPS)

01:39:45.347 --> 01:39:46.414
(SCREAMING)

01:40:15.143 --> 01:40:16.444
(ACCELERATING)

01:40:40.468 --> 01:40:41.603
Doc.

01:41:30.485 --> 01:41:32.120
(SHOUTING GLEEFULLY)

01:41:42.864 --> 01:41:44.532
(HELICOPTER HOVERING)

01:41:58.880 --> 01:42:00.548
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

01:42:02.650 --> 01:42:03.751
(EXPLOSIVE CRASHING)

01:42:05.787 --> 01:42:06.921
(TIRES SQUEALING)

01:42:06.954 --> 01:42:08.190
(CRASHING)

01:42:18.233 --> 01:42:19.834
Crazy drunk driver.

01:42:30.578 --> 01:42:31.779
Whoo!

01:42:35.517 --> 01:42:37.452
All right. Fred.

01:42:39.454 --> 01:42:41.623
You look great.
Everything looks great.

01:42:43.491 --> 01:42:46.794
1:24. I still got time.
I'm coming, Doc!

01:42:48.730 --> 01:42:51.233
(ENGINE DYING)

01:42:51.266 --> 01:42:55.903
No! No, not again!
Come on! Come on!

01:42:55.937 --> 01:42:57.171
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:43:01.243 --> 01:43:01.943
(TERRORISTS SHOUTING
INDISTINCTLY)

01:43:09.251 --> 01:43:10.485
Libyans.

01:43:33.275 --> 01:43:33.941
MARTY: No!

01:43:35.743 --> 01:43:36.844
You bastard!

01:43:50.558 --> 01:43:51.659
TERRORIST: Go!

01:43:58.633 --> 01:43:59.867
(GUN FIRING)

01:44:18.320 --> 01:44:19.621
(TERRORISTS SCREAMING)

01:44:26.093 --> 01:44:27.962
Doc! Doc!

01:44:31.633 --> 01:44:32.634
(SOBBING)

01:44:33.835 --> 01:44:35.737
No! No!

01:44:50.852 --> 01:44:52.019
You're alive.

01:45:01.696 --> 01:45:02.930
Bulletproof vest?

01:45:04.666 --> 01:45:05.933
How did you know?

01:45:07.602 --> 01:45:09.070
I never got a chance
to tell you.

01:45:23.885 --> 01:45:27.121
What about all that talk
about screwing up
future events?

01:45:27.154 --> 01:45:29.924
The space-time continuum?

01:45:29.957 --> 01:45:32.360
Well, I figured,
what the hell?

01:45:43.037 --> 01:45:45.072
So, how far ahead
are you going?

01:45:45.106 --> 01:45:48.710
About 30 years.
It's a nice, round number.

01:45:48.743 --> 01:45:52.414
Look me up when you
get there, all right?
Guess I'll be about 47.

01:45:52.647 --> 01:45:53.648
I will.

01:45:54.048 --> 01:45:55.383
Take care.

01:45:56.183 --> 01:45:57.752
You, too.

01:45:57.785 --> 01:46:00.888
Right. Bye-bye, Einie.

01:46:00.922 --> 01:46:03.090
Oh. And watch that re-entry.
It's a little bumpy.

01:46:04.058 --> 01:46:05.092
You bet.

01:46:26.013 --> 01:46:27.114
(EXPLOSIVE CRASHING)

01:46:43.731 --> 01:46:44.732
(POP SONG PLAYING ON RADIO)

01:47:10.492 --> 01:47:11.893
What a nightmare.

01:47:24.138 --> 01:47:27.008
LINDA: If Paul calls me,
tell him I'm working at
the boutique late tonight.

01:47:27.041 --> 01:47:28.843
DAVID: Linda, first of all,
I'm not your
answering service,

01:47:28.876 --> 01:47:30.845
second of all,
somebody named Greg

01:47:30.878 --> 01:47:32.514
or Craig called you
just a little while ago.

01:47:32.547 --> 01:47:34.215
Well, which one was it,
Greg or Craig?

01:47:34.248 --> 01:47:36.551
I don't know!
I can't keep up with
all of your boyfriends.

01:47:36.584 --> 01:47:37.552
Hey.

01:47:39.020 --> 01:47:40.187
What the hell is this?

01:47:41.188 --> 01:47:43.791
Breakfast.

01:47:43.825 --> 01:47:45.226
DAVID: Did you sleep
in your clothes
again last night?

01:47:45.259 --> 01:47:46.494
Yeah. I...

01:47:47.962 --> 01:47:50.865
Yeah. What are
you wearing, Dave?

01:47:50.898 --> 01:47:53.100
Marty, I always wear
a suit to the office.

01:47:55.169 --> 01:47:56.804
You all right?
Yeah.

01:47:58.039 --> 01:47:58.940
LORRAINE: I think we
need a rematch, George.

01:47:58.973 --> 01:48:00.074
A rematch?

01:48:00.107 --> 01:48:01.075
Why? Were you cheating?

01:48:01.108 --> 01:48:02.510
(LAUGHING) No.

01:48:02.544 --> 01:48:03.911
Hello.
Good morning.

01:48:06.180 --> 01:48:08.550
Mom! Dad!

01:48:08.583 --> 01:48:10.051
Did you hit your head?
Marty, are you all right?

01:48:10.084 --> 01:48:14.188
You guys look great.
Mom, you look so thin.

01:48:14.221 --> 01:48:16.257
Why, thank you, Marty.
George!

01:48:17.058 --> 01:48:18.225
(SIGHS)

01:48:18.259 --> 01:48:19.961
Good morning,
sleepyhead.

01:48:21.162 --> 01:48:22.597
Good morning, Dave.
Linda.

01:48:22.830 --> 01:48:24.298
DAVID: Good morning, Mom.

01:48:24.331 --> 01:48:27.034
LINDA:
Marty, I almost forgot.
Jennifer Parker called.

01:48:27.068 --> 01:48:31.072
I sure like her, Marty.
She is such a sweet girl.

01:48:31.105 --> 01:48:32.907
Isn't tonight the night
of the big date?

01:48:32.940 --> 01:48:35.276
What? What, Ma?

01:48:35.309 --> 01:48:36.578
Aren't you going up
to the lake tonight?

01:48:36.611 --> 01:48:39.847
You've been planning it
for two weeks.

01:48:39.881 --> 01:48:41.983
Mom, we talked about this.
How can I go to the lake?

01:48:42.016 --> 01:48:43.150
The car's wrecked.

01:48:43.184 --> 01:48:45.119
Wrecked?
Wrecked?

01:48:45.152 --> 01:48:45.953
When did this happen?
Why wasn't I told?

01:48:45.987 --> 01:48:47.154
Quiet down.

01:48:47.188 --> 01:48:49.190
I'm sure the car is fine.

01:48:49.223 --> 01:48:51.325
DAVID: Why am I always
the last one to know
about these things?

01:48:51.358 --> 01:48:54.596
See? There's Biff
out there waxing
it right now.

01:48:54.829 --> 01:48:56.598
Now, Biff, I want
to make sure that

01:48:56.631 --> 01:48:59.200
we get two coats
of wax this time,
not just one.

01:48:59.233 --> 01:49:00.935
I'm just finishing up
the second coat now.

01:49:00.968 --> 01:49:02.970
Now, Biff,
don't con me.

01:49:04.839 --> 01:49:07.341
I'm sorry, Mr. McFly.

01:49:07.374 --> 01:49:09.611
I meant
I was just starting
on the second coat.

01:49:11.378 --> 01:49:15.683
Biff. What a character.
Always trying to get
away with something.

01:49:15.717 --> 01:49:18.352
I've had to stay
on top of Biff ever
since high school.

01:49:18.385 --> 01:49:20.655
Although,
if it wasn't for him...

01:49:20.888 --> 01:49:22.123
We never would
have fallen in love.

01:49:22.156 --> 01:49:24.592
That's right.

01:49:24.626 --> 01:49:27.361
Mr. McFly! Mr. McFly,
this just arrived.

01:49:27.394 --> 01:49:29.563
Oh, hi, Marty.
I think it's your
new book.

01:49:32.634 --> 01:49:36.370
Honey!
Your first novel.

01:49:36.403 --> 01:49:38.005
GEORGE: Like I've
always told you,

01:49:39.140 --> 01:49:40.675
you put your mind to it,
you can accomplish anything.

01:49:40.708 --> 01:49:43.310
Oh, Marty,
here's your keys.

01:49:43.344 --> 01:49:44.578
You're all waxed up,
ready for tonight.

01:49:45.279 --> 01:49:46.213
Keys?

01:50:03.097 --> 01:50:04.398
How about a ride,
mister?

01:50:04.431 --> 01:50:07.268
Jennifer.

01:50:07.301 --> 01:50:12.106
Oh, are you a sight
for sore eyes!
Let me look at you.

01:50:12.139 --> 01:50:14.341
Marty, you're acting
like you haven't
seen me in a week.

01:50:14.375 --> 01:50:16.678
I haven't.

01:50:16.911 --> 01:50:19.380
You okay?
Is everything all right?

01:50:23.084 --> 01:50:24.018
MARTY: Oh, yeah.

01:50:26.420 --> 01:50:28.022
Everything is great.

01:50:31.025 --> 01:50:32.059
(EXPLOSIVE CRASHING)

01:50:34.095 --> 01:50:35.162
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:50:42.937 --> 01:50:46.340
Marty!
You've got to come
back with me!

01:50:47.308 --> 01:50:48.743
Where?

01:50:48.776 --> 01:50:49.677
Back to the future.

01:50:55.082 --> 01:50:56.350
Wait a minute.
What are you doing, Doc?

01:50:57.484 --> 01:50:58.385
I need fuel.

01:51:02.489 --> 01:51:05.059
Go ahead. Quick!
Get in the car.

01:51:05.092 --> 01:51:07.428
No, no. Doc,
I just got here, okay?

01:51:07.461 --> 01:51:09.196
Jennifer's here.
We're gonna take
the new truck for a spin.

01:51:09.230 --> 01:51:12.734
Well, bring her along.
This concerns her, too.

01:51:12.767 --> 01:51:14.201
Wait a minute, Doc.
What are you
talking about?

01:51:14.235 --> 01:51:16.303
What happens to us
in the future?

01:51:16.337 --> 01:51:18.039
Do we become assholes
or something?

01:51:18.072 --> 01:51:19.373
No, no, no,
no, Marty.

01:51:19.406 --> 01:51:21.075
Both you and Jennifer
turn out fine.

01:51:21.108 --> 01:51:23.210
It's your kids, Marty.

01:51:23.244 --> 01:51:25.112
Something has
got to be done
about your kids.

01:51:25.146 --> 01:51:26.447
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:51:31.986 --> 01:51:34.756
Hey, Doc, we better back up.
We don't have enough
road to get up to 88.

01:51:34.789 --> 01:51:38.225
Roads? Where we're going,
we don't need roads.

01:51:41.262 --> 01:51:42.296
(JETS FIRING)
